42 //
43 // Most object types in the V8 JavaScript are described in this file.
44 //
45 // Inheritance hierarchy:
46 // - Object
47 // - Smi (immediate small integer)
48 // - HeapObject (superclass for everything allocated in the heap)
49 // - JSReceiver (suitable for property access)
50 // - JSObject
51 // - JSArray
52 // - JSArrayBuffer
53 // - JSArrayBufferView
54 // - JSTypedArray
55 // - JSDataView
56 // - JSBoundFunction
57 // - JSCollection
58 // - JSSet
59 // - JSMap
60 // - JSStringIterator
61 // - JSSetIterator
62 // - JSMapIterator
63 // - JSWeakCollection
64 // - JSWeakMap
65 // - JSWeakSet
66 // - JSRegExp
67 // - JSFunction
68 // - JSGeneratorObject
69 // - JSGlobalObject
70 // - JSGlobalProxy
71 // - JSValue
72 // - JSDate
73 // - JSMessageObject
74 // - JSModuleNamespace
75 // - JSFixedArrayIterator
76 // - JSProxy
77 // - FixedArrayBase
78 // - ByteArray
79 // - BytecodeArray
80 // - FixedArray
81 // - DescriptorArray
82 // - FrameArray
83 // - LiteralsArray
84 // - HashTable
85 // - Dictionary
86 // - StringTable
87 // - StringSet
88 // - CompilationCacheTable
89 // - CodeCacheHashTable
90 // - MapCache
91 // - OrderedHashTable
92 // - OrderedHashSet
93 // - OrderedHashMap
94 // - Context
95 // - TypeFeedbackMetadata
96 // - TypeFeedbackVector
97 // - TemplateList
98 // - TransitionArray
99 // - ScopeInfo
100 // - ModuleInfoEntry
101 // - ModuleInfo
102 // - ScriptContextTable
103 // - WeakFixedArray
104 // - FixedDoubleArray
105 // - Name
106 // - String
107 // - SeqString
108 // - SeqOneByteString
109 // - SeqTwoByteString
110 // - SlicedString
111 // - ConsString
112 // - ExternalString
113 // - ExternalOneByteString
114 // - ExternalTwoByteString
115 // - InternalizedString
116 // - SeqInternalizedString
117 // - SeqOneByteInternalizedString
118 // - SeqTwoByteInternalizedString
119 // - ConsInternalizedString
120 // - ExternalInternalizedString
121 // - ExternalOneByteInternalizedString
122 // - ExternalTwoByteInternalizedString
123 // - Symbol
124 // - HeapNumber
125 // - Simd128Value
126 // - Float32x4
127 // - Int32x4
128 // - Uint32x4
129 // - Bool32x4
130 // - Int16x8
131 // - Uint16x8
132 // - Bool16x8
133 // - Int8x16
134 // - Uint8x16
135 // - Bool8x16
136 // - Cell
137 // - PropertyCell
138 // - Code
139 // - AbstractCode, a wrapper around Code or BytecodeArray
140 // - Map
141 // - Oddball
142 // - Foreign
143 // - SharedFunctionInfo
144 // - Struct
145 // - Box
146 // - AccessorInfo
147 // - PromiseResolveThenableJobInfo
148 // - PromiseReactionJobInfo
149 // - AccessorPair
150 // - AccessCheckInfo
151 // - InterceptorInfo
152 // - CallHandlerInfo
153 // - TemplateInfo
154 // - FunctionTemplateInfo
155 // - ObjectTemplateInfo
156 // - Script
157 // - DebugInfo
158 // - BreakPointInfo
159 // - CodeCache
160 // - PrototypeInfo
161 // - Module
162 // - WeakCell
163 //
164 // Formats of Object*:
165 // Smi: [31 bit signed int] 0
166 // HeapObject: [32 bit direct pointer] (4 byte aligned) | 01

171 enum KeyedAccessStoreMode {
172  STANDARD_STORE,
173  STORE_TRANSITION_TO_OBJECT,
174  STORE_TRANSITION_TO_DOUBLE,
175  STORE_AND_GROW_NO_TRANSITION,
176  STORE_AND_GROW_TRANSITION_TO_OBJECT,
177  STORE_AND_GROW_TRANSITION_TO_DOUBLE,
178  STORE_NO_TRANSITION_IGNORE_OUT_OF_BOUNDS,
179  STORE_NO_TRANSITION_HANDLE_COW
180 };

205 static inline bool IsTransitionStoreMode(KeyedAccessStoreMode store_mode) {
206  return store_mode == STORE_TRANSITION_TO_OBJECT ||
207  store_mode == STORE_TRANSITION_TO_DOUBLE ||
208  store_mode == STORE_AND_GROW_TRANSITION_TO_OBJECT ||
209  store_mode == STORE_AND_GROW_TRANSITION_TO_DOUBLE;
210 }
211 
212 
213 static inline KeyedAccessStoreMode GetNonTransitioningStoreMode(
214  KeyedAccessStoreMode store_mode) {
215  if (store_mode >= STORE_NO_TRANSITION_IGNORE_OUT_OF_BOUNDS) {
216  return store_mode;
217  }
218  if (store_mode >= STORE_AND_GROW_NO_TRANSITION) {
219  return STORE_AND_GROW_NO_TRANSITION;
220  }
221  return STANDARD_STORE;
222 }
223 
224 
225 static inline bool IsGrowStoreMode(KeyedAccessStoreMode store_mode) {
226  return store_mode >= STORE_AND_GROW_NO_TRANSITION &&
227  store_mode <= STORE_AND_GROW_TRANSITION_TO_DOUBLE;
228 }

234 // SKIP_WRITE_BARRIER skips the write barrier.
235 // UPDATE_WEAK_WRITE_BARRIER skips the marking part of the write barrier and
236 // only performs the generational part.
237 // UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER is doing the full barrier, marking and generational.
238 enum WriteBarrierMode {
239  SKIP_WRITE_BARRIER,
240  UPDATE_WEAK_WRITE_BARRIER,
241  UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER
242 };

257 // Indicates how aggressively the prototype should be optimized. FAST_PROTOTYPE
258 // will give the fastest result by tailoring the map to the prototype, but that
259 // will cause polymorphism with other objects. REGULAR_PROTOTYPE is to be used
260 // (at least for now) when dynamically modifying the prototype chain of an
261 // object using __proto__ or Object.setPrototypeOf.
262 enum PrototypeOptimizationMode { REGULAR_PROTOTYPE, FAST_PROTOTYPE };

267  INSERT_TRANSITION,
268  OMIT_TRANSITION
269 };

272 // Indicates whether the transition is simple: the target map of the transition
273 // either extends the current map with a new property, or it modifies the
274 // property that was added last to the current map.
275 enum SimpleTransitionFlag {
276  SIMPLE_PROPERTY_TRANSITION,
277  PROPERTY_TRANSITION,
278  SPECIAL_TRANSITION
279 };

282 // Indicates whether we are only interested in the descriptors of a particular
283 // map, or in all descriptors in the descriptor array.
284 enum DescriptorFlag {
285  ALL_DESCRIPTORS,
286  OWN_DESCRIPTORS
287 };
288 
289 // The GC maintains a bit of information, the MarkingParity, which toggles
290 // from odd to even and back every time marking is completed. Incremental
291 // marking can visit an object twice during a marking phase, so algorithms that
292 // that piggy-back on marking can use the parity to ensure that they only
293 // perform an operation on an object once per marking phase: they record the
294 // MarkingParity when they visit an object, and only re-visit the object when it
295 // is marked again and the MarkingParity changes.
296 enum MarkingParity {
297  NO_MARKING_PARITY,
298  ODD_MARKING_PARITY,
299  EVEN_MARKING_PARITY
300 };

302 // ICs store extra state in a Code object. The default extra state is
303 // kNoExtraICState.
304 typedef int ExtraICState;
305 static const ExtraICState kNoExtraICState = 0;

310 // We may store the unsigned bit field as signed Smi value and do not
311 // use the sign bit.
312 const int kStubMajorKeyBits = 8;
313 const int kStubMinorKeyBits = kSmiValueSize - kStubMajorKeyBits - 1;

315 // All Maps have a field instance_type containing a InstanceType.
316 // It describes the type of the instances.
317 //
318 // As an example, a JavaScript object is a heap object and its map
319 // instance_type is JS_OBJECT_TYPE.
320 //
321 // The names of the string instance types are intended to systematically
322 // mirror their encoding in the instance_type field of the map. The default
323 // encoding is considered TWO_BYTE. It is not mentioned in the name. ONE_BYTE
324 // encoding is mentioned explicitly in the name. Likewise, the default
325 // representation is considered sequential. It is not mentioned in the
326 // name. The other representations (e.g. CONS, EXTERNAL) are explicitly
327 // mentioned. Finally, the string is either a STRING_TYPE (if it is a normal
328 // string) or a INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE (if it is a internalized string).
329 //
330 // NOTE: The following things are some that depend on the string types having
331 // instance_types that are less than those of all other types:
332 // HeapObject::Size, HeapObject::IterateBody, the typeof operator, and
333 // Object::IsString.
334 //
335 // NOTE: Everything following JS_VALUE_TYPE is considered a
336 // JSObject for GC purposes. The first four entries here have typeof
337 // 'object', whereas JS_FUNCTION_TYPE has typeof 'function'.
338 #define INSTANCE_TYPE_LIST(V) \
339  V(STRING_TYPE) \
340  V(ONE_BYTE_STRING_TYPE) \
341  V(CONS_STRING_TYPE) \
342  V(CONS_ONE_BYTE_STRING_TYPE) \

543 // A struct is a simple object a set of object-valued fields. Including an
544 // object type in this causes the compiler to generate most of the boilerplate
545 // code for the class including allocation and garbage collection routines,
546 // casts and predicates. All you need to define is the class, methods and
547 // object verification routines. Easy, no?
548 //
549 // Note that for subtle reasons related to the ordering or numerical values of
550 // type tags, elements in this list have to be added to the INSTANCE_TYPE_LIST
551 // manually.
552 #define STRUCT_LIST(V) \
553  V(BOX, Box, box) \
554  V(PROMISE_RESOLVE_THENABLE_JOB_INFO, PromiseResolveThenableJobInfo, \
555  promise_resolve_thenable_job_info) \
556  V(PROMISE_REACTION_JOB_INFO, PromiseReactionJobInfo, \
557  promise_reaction_job_info) \
558  V(ACCESSOR_INFO, AccessorInfo, accessor_info) \
559  V(ACCESSOR_PAIR, AccessorPair, accessor_pair) \
560  V(ACCESS_CHECK_INFO, AccessCheckInfo, access_check_info) \
561  V(INTERCEPTOR_INFO, InterceptorInfo, interceptor_info) \
562  V(CALL_HANDLER_INFO, CallHandlerInfo, call_handler_info) \
563  V(FUNCTION_TEMPLATE_INFO, FunctionTemplateInfo, function_template_info) \
564  V(OBJECT_TEMPLATE_INFO, ObjectTemplateInfo, object_template_info) \
565  V(SCRIPT, Script, script) \
566  V(ALLOCATION_SITE, AllocationSite, allocation_site) \
567  V(ALLOCATION_MEMENTO, AllocationMemento, allocation_memento) \
568  V(TYPE_FEEDBACK_INFO, TypeFeedbackInfo, type_feedback_info) \
569  V(ALIASED_ARGUMENTS_ENTRY, AliasedArgumentsEntry, aliased_arguments_entry) \
570  V(DEBUG_INFO, DebugInfo, debug_info) \
571  V(BREAK_POINT_INFO, BreakPointInfo, break_point_info) \
572  V(PROTOTYPE_INFO, PrototypeInfo, prototype_info) \
573  V(TUPLE3, Tuple3, tuple3) \
574  V(MODULE, Module, module) \
575  V(CONTEXT_EXTENSION, ContextExtension, context_extension)
576 
577 // We use the full 8 bits of the instance_type field to encode heap object
578 // instance types. The high-order bit (bit 7) is set if the object is not a
579 // string, and cleared if it is a string.
580 const uint32_t kIsNotStringMask = 0x80;
581 const uint32_t kStringTag = 0x0;
582 const uint32_t kNotStringTag = 0x80;
583 
584 // Bit 6 indicates that the object is an internalized string (if set) or not.
585 // Bit 7 has to be clear as well.
586 const uint32_t kIsNotInternalizedMask = 0x40;
587 const uint32_t kNotInternalizedTag = 0x40;
588 const uint32_t kInternalizedTag = 0x0;
589 
590 // If bit 7 is clear then bit 2 indicates whether the string consists of
591 // two-byte characters or one-byte characters.
592 const uint32_t kStringEncodingMask = 0x4;
593 const uint32_t kTwoByteStringTag = 0x0;
594 const uint32_t kOneByteStringTag = 0x4;
595 
596 // If bit 7 is clear, the low-order 2 bits indicate the representation
597 // of the string.
598 const uint32_t kStringRepresentationMask = 0x03;
599 enum StringRepresentationTag {
600  kSeqStringTag = 0x0,
601  kConsStringTag = 0x1,
602  kExternalStringTag = 0x2,
603  kSlicedStringTag = 0x3
604 };
605 const uint32_t kIsIndirectStringMask = 0x1;
606 const uint32_t kIsIndirectStringTag = 0x1;
607 STATIC_ASSERT((kSeqStringTag & kIsIndirectStringMask) == 0); // NOLINT
608 STATIC_ASSERT((kExternalStringTag & kIsIndirectStringMask) == 0); // NOLINT
609 STATIC_ASSERT((kConsStringTag &
610  kIsIndirectStringMask) == kIsIndirectStringTag); // NOLINT
611 STATIC_ASSERT((kSlicedStringTag &
612  kIsIndirectStringMask) == kIsIndirectStringTag); // NOLINT
613 
614 // Use this mask to distinguish between cons and slice only after making
615 // sure that the string is one of the two (an indirect string).
616 const uint32_t kSlicedNotConsMask = kSlicedStringTag & ~kConsStringTag;
617 STATIC_ASSERT(IS_POWER_OF_TWO(kSlicedNotConsMask));
618 
619 // If bit 7 is clear, then bit 3 indicates whether this two-byte
620 // string actually contains one byte data.
621 const uint32_t kOneByteDataHintMask = 0x08;
622 const uint32_t kOneByteDataHintTag = 0x08;
623 
624 // If bit 7 is clear and string representation indicates an external string,
625 // then bit 4 indicates whether the data pointer is cached.
626 const uint32_t kShortExternalStringMask = 0x10;
627 const uint32_t kShortExternalStringTag = 0x10;
628 
629 
630 // A ConsString with an empty string as the right side is a candidate
631 // for being shortcut by the garbage collector. We don't allocate any
632 // non-flat internalized strings, so we do not shortcut them thereby
633 // avoiding turning internalized strings into strings. The bit-masks
634 // below contain the internalized bit as additional safety.
635 // See heap.cc, mark-compact.cc and objects-visiting.cc.
636 const uint32_t kShortcutTypeMask =
637  kIsNotStringMask |
638  kIsNotInternalizedMask |
639  kStringRepresentationMask;
640 const uint32_t kShortcutTypeTag = kConsStringTag | kNotInternalizedTag;
641 
642 static inline bool IsShortcutCandidate(int type) {
643  return ((type & kShortcutTypeMask) == kShortcutTypeTag);
644 }
645 
646 enum InstanceType {
647  // String types.
648  INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE = kTwoByteStringTag | kSeqStringTag |
649  kInternalizedTag, // FIRST_PRIMITIVE_TYPE
650  ONE_BYTE_INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE =
651  kOneByteStringTag | kSeqStringTag | kInternalizedTag,
652  EXTERNAL_INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE =
653  kTwoByteStringTag | kExternalStringTag | kInternalizedTag,
654  EXTERNAL_ONE_BYTE_INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE =
655  kOneByteStringTag | kExternalStringTag | kInternalizedTag,
656  EXTERNAL_INTERNALIZED_STRING_WITH_ONE_BYTE_DATA_TYPE =

658  kInternalizedTag,

660  kShortExternalStringTag |
661  kInternalizedTag,

663  EXTERNAL_ONE_BYTE_INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE | kShortExternalStringTag |
664  kInternalizedTag,
665  SHORT_EXTERNAL_INTERNALIZED_STRING_WITH_ONE_BYTE_DATA_TYPE =
666  EXTERNAL_INTERNALIZED_STRING_WITH_ONE_BYTE_DATA_TYPE |
667  kShortExternalStringTag | kInternalizedTag,
668  STRING_TYPE = INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE | kNotInternalizedTag,
669  ONE_BYTE_STRING_TYPE =
670  ONE_BYTE_INTERNALIZED_STRING_TYPE | kNotInternalizedTag,
671  CONS_STRING_TYPE = kTwoByteStringTag | kConsStringTag | kNotInternalizedTag,
672  CONS_ONE_BYTE_STRING_TYPE =
673  kOneByteStringTag | kConsStringTag | kNotInternalizedTag,
674  SLICED_STRING_TYPE =
675  kTwoByteStringTag | kSlicedStringTag | kNotInternalizedTag,

876 
877  FIRST_ARRAY_ITERATOR_TYPE = FIRST_ARRAY_KEY_ITERATOR_TYPE,
878  LAST_ARRAY_ITERATOR_TYPE = LAST_ARRAY_VALUE_ITERATOR_TYPE,
879 };

953 // Result of an abstract relational comparison of x and y, implemented according

957  kEqual, // x = y

1183 // Object is the abstract superclass for all classes in the
1184 // object hierarchy.
1185 // Object does not use any virtual functions to avoid the
1186 // allocation of the C++ vtable.

1188 // data members can be present in Object.

1203  // A non-keyed store is of the form a.x = foo or a["x"] = foo whereas
1204  // a keyed store is of the form a[expression] = foo.

1210  enum ShouldThrow { THROW_ON_ERROR, DONT_THROW };

1212 #define RETURN_FAILURE(isolate, should_throw, call) \
1213  do { \
1214  if ((should_throw) == DONT_THROW) { \
1215  return Just(false); \
1216  } else { \
1217  isolate->Throw(*isolate->factory()->call); \
1218  return Nothing<bool>(); \
1219  } \
1220  } while (false)
1221 
1222 #define MAYBE_RETURN(call, value) \
1223  do { \
1224  if ((call).IsNothing()) return value; \
1225  } while (false)
1226 
1227 #define MAYBE_RETURN_NULL(call) MAYBE_RETURN(call, MaybeHandle<Object>())

1589 // Smi represents integer Numbers that can be stored in 31 bits.
1590 // Smis are immediate which means they are NOT allocated in the heap.
1591 // The this pointer has the following format: [31 bit signed int] 0
1592 // For long smis it has the following format:
1593 // [32 bit signed int] [31 bits zero padding] 0
1594 // Smi stands for small integer.
1595 class Smi: public Object {
1596  public:
1597  // Returns the integer value.
1598  inline int value() const { return Internals::SmiValue(this); }
1599 
1600  // Convert a value to a Smi object.
1601  static inline Smi* FromInt(int value) {
1602  DCHECK(Smi::IsValid(value));
1603  return reinterpret_cast<Smi*>(Internals::IntToSmi(value));
1604  }
1605 
1606  static inline Smi* FromIntptr(intptr_t value) {
1607  DCHECK(Smi::IsValid(value));
1608  int smi_shift_bits = kSmiTagSize + kSmiShiftSize;
1609  return reinterpret_cast<Smi*>((value << smi_shift_bits) | kSmiTag);
1610  }
1611 
1612  // Returns whether value can be represented in a Smi.
1613  static inline bool IsValid(intptr_t value) {
1614  bool result = Internals::IsValidSmi(value);
1615  DCHECK_EQ(result, value >= kMinValue && value <= kMaxValue);
1616  return result;
1617  }
1618 
1619  DECLARE_CAST(Smi)
1620 
1621  // Dispatched behavior.
1622  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE void SmiPrint(std::ostream& os) const; // NOLINT
1623  DECLARE_VERIFIER(Smi)
1624 
1625  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE static Smi* const kZero;
1626  static const int kMinValue =
1627  (static_cast<unsigned int>(-1)) << (kSmiValueSize - 1);
1628  static const int kMaxValue = -(kMinValue + 1);
1629 
1630  private:
1631  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(Smi);
1632 };
1633 
1634 
1635 // Heap objects typically have a map pointer in their first word. However,
1636 // during GC other data (e.g. mark bits, forwarding addresses) is sometimes
1637 // encoded in the first word. The class MapWord is an abstraction of the
1638 // value in a heap object's first word.
1639 class MapWord BASE_EMBEDDED {
1640  public:
1641  // Normal state: the map word contains a map pointer.
1642 
1643  // Create a map word from a map pointer.
1644  static inline MapWord FromMap(const Map* map);
1645 
1646  // View this map word as a map pointer.
1647  inline Map* ToMap();
1648 
1649 
1650  // Scavenge collection: the map word of live objects in the from space
1651  // contains a forwarding address (a heap object pointer in the to space).
1652 
1653  // True if this map word is a forwarding address for a scavenge
1654  // collection. Only valid during a scavenge collection (specifically,
1655  // when all map words are heap object pointers, i.e. not during a full GC).
1656  inline bool IsForwardingAddress() const;
1657 
1658  // Create a map word from a forwarding address.
1659  static inline MapWord FromForwardingAddress(HeapObject* object);
1660 
1661  // View this map word as a forwarding address.
1662  inline HeapObject* ToForwardingAddress();
1663 
1664  static inline MapWord FromRawValue(uintptr_t value) {
1665  return MapWord(value);
1666  }
1667 
1668  inline uintptr_t ToRawValue() {
1669  return value_;
1670  }
1671 
1672  private:
1673  // HeapObject calls the private constructor and directly reads the value.
1674  friend class HeapObject;
1675 
1676  explicit MapWord(uintptr_t value) : value_(value) {}
1677 
1678  uintptr_t value_;
1679 };
1680 
1681 
1682 // HeapObject is the superclass for all classes describing heap allocated
1683 // objects.
1684 class HeapObject: public Object {
1685  public:
1686  // [map]: Contains a map which contains the object's reflective
1687  // information.
1688  inline Map* map() const;
1689  inline void set_map(Map* value);
1690  // The no-write-barrier version. This is OK if the object is white and in
1691  // new space, or if the value is an immortal immutable object, like the maps
1692  // of primitive (non-JS) objects like strings, heap numbers etc.
1693  inline void set_map_no_write_barrier(Map* value);
1694 
1695  // Get the map using acquire load.
1696  inline Map* synchronized_map();
1697  inline MapWord synchronized_map_word() const;
1698 
1699  // Set the map using release store
1700  inline void synchronized_set_map(Map* value);

1838 // The HeapNumber class describes heap allocated numbers that cannot be
1839 // represented in a Smi (small integer)
1840 class HeapNumber: public HeapObject {
1841  public:
1842  // [value]: number value.
1843  inline double value() const;
1844  inline void set_value(double value);
1845 
1846  DECLARE_CAST(HeapNumber)
1847 
1848  // Dispatched behavior.
1849  bool HeapNumberBooleanValue();
1850 
1851  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE void HeapNumberPrint(std::ostream& os); // NOLINT
1852  DECLARE_VERIFIER(HeapNumber)
1853 
1854  inline int get_exponent();
1855  inline int get_sign();
1856 
1857  // Layout description.
1858  static const int kValueOffset = HeapObject::kHeaderSize;
1859  // IEEE doubles are two 32 bit words. The first is just mantissa, the second
1860  // is a mixture of sign, exponent and mantissa. The offsets of two 32 bit
1861  // words within double numbers are endian dependent and they are set
1862  // accordingly.
1863 #if defined(V8_TARGET_LITTLE_ENDIAN)
1864  static const int kMantissaOffset = kValueOffset;
1865  static const int kExponentOffset = kValueOffset + 4;
1866 #elif defined(V8_TARGET_BIG_ENDIAN)
1867  static const int kMantissaOffset = kValueOffset + 4;
1868  static const int kExponentOffset = kValueOffset;
1869 #else
1870 #error Unknown byte ordering
1871 #endif
1872 
1873  static const int kSize = kValueOffset + kDoubleSize;
1874  static const uint32_t kSignMask = 0x80000000u;
1875  static const uint32_t kExponentMask = 0x7ff00000u;
1876  static const uint32_t kMantissaMask = 0xfffffu;
1877  static const int kMantissaBits = 52;
1878  static const int kExponentBits = 11;
1879  static const int kExponentBias = 1023;
1880  static const int kExponentShift = 20;
1881  static const int kInfinityOrNanExponent =
1882  (kExponentMask >> kExponentShift) - kExponentBias;
1883  static const int kMantissaBitsInTopWord = 20;
1884  static const int kNonMantissaBitsInTopWord = 12;
1885 
1886  private:
1887  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(HeapNumber);
1888 };

2172 // The JSObject describes real heap allocated JavaScript objects with
2173 // properties.
2174 // Note that the map of JSObject changes during execution to enable inline
2175 // caching.
2176 class JSObject: public JSReceiver {
2177  public:

2179  Handle<JSFunction> constructor, Handle<JSReceiver> new_target,

2187  // [elements]: The elements (properties with names that are integers).
2188  //
2189  // Elements can be in two general modes: fast and slow. Each mode
2190  // corresponds to a set of object representations of elements that
2191  // have something in common.
2192  //
2193  // In the fast mode elements is a FixedArray and so each element can
2194  // be quickly accessed. This fact is used in the generated code. The
2195  // elements array can have one of three maps in this mode:
2196  // fixed_array_map, sloppy_arguments_elements_map or
2197  // fixed_cow_array_map (for copy-on-write arrays). In the latter case
2198  // the elements array may be shared by a few objects and so before
2199  // writing to any element the array must be copied. Use
2200  // EnsureWritableFastElements in this case.
2201  //
2202  // In the slow mode the elements is either a NumberDictionary, a
2203  // FixedArray parameter map for a (sloppy) arguments object.
2204  DECL_ACCESSORS(elements, FixedArrayBase)
2205  inline void initialize_elements();
2206  static void ResetElements(Handle<JSObject> object);
2207  static inline void SetMapAndElements(Handle<JSObject> object,
2208  Handle<Map> map,
2209  Handle<FixedArrayBase> elements);

2211  ElementsAccessor* GetElementsAccessor();

2213  inline bool HasFastSmiElements();
2214  // Returns true if an object has elements of FAST_ELEMENTS ElementsKind.
2215  inline bool HasFastObjectElements();
2216  // Returns true if an object has elements of FAST_ELEMENTS or
2217  // FAST_SMI_ONLY_ELEMENTS.
2218  inline bool HasFastSmiOrObjectElements();
2219  // Returns true if an object has any of the fast elements kinds.
2220  inline bool HasFastElements();
2221  // Returns true if an object has elements of FAST_DOUBLE_ELEMENTS
2222  // ElementsKind.
2223  inline bool HasFastDoubleElements();
2224  // Returns true if an object has elements of FAST_HOLEY_*_ELEMENTS
2225  // ElementsKind.
2226  inline bool HasFastHoleyElements();

2821 // FixedArray describes fixed-sized arrays with element type Object*.

2875  DECLARE_CAST(FixedArray)

2877  // Maximal allowed size, in bytes, of a single FixedArray.
2878  // Prevents overflowing size computations, as well as extreme memory
2879  // consumption.
2880  static const int kMaxSize = 128 * MB * kPointerSize;

3190 // DescriptorArrays are fixed arrays used to hold instance descriptors.
3191 // The format of the these objects is:

3399 // HashTable is a subclass of FixedArray that implements a hash table
3400 // that uses open addressing and quadratic probing.
3401 //
3402 // In order for the quadratic probing to work, elements that have not
3403 // yet been used and elements that have been deleted are
3404 // distinguished. Probing continues when deleted elements are
3405 // encountered and stops when unused elements are encountered.
3406 //
3407 // - Elements with key == undefined have not been used yet.
3408 // - Elements with key == the_hole have been deleted.
3409 //
3410 // The hash table class is parameterized with a Shape and a Key.
3411 // Shape must be a class with the following interface:
3412 // class ExampleShape {
3413 // public:
3414 // // Tells whether key matches other.
3415 // static bool IsMatch(Key key, Object* other);
3416 // // Returns the hash value for key.
3417 // static uint32_t Hash(Key key);
3418 // // Returns the hash value for object.
3419 // static uint32_t HashForObject(Key key, Object* object);
3420 // // Convert key to an object.
3421 // static inline Handle<Object> AsHandle(Isolate* isolate, Key key);
3422 // // The prefix size indicates number of elements in the beginning
3423 // // of the backing storage.
3424 // static const int kPrefixSize = ..;
3425 // // The Element size indicates number of elements per entry.
3426 // static const int kEntrySize = ..;
3427 // };
3428 // The prefix size indicates an amount of memory in the
3429 // beginning of the backing storage that can be used for non-element
3430 // information by subclasses.
3431 
3432 template<typename Key>
3433 class BaseShape {
3434  public:
3435  static const bool UsesSeed = false;
3436  static uint32_t Hash(Key key) { return 0; }
3437  static uint32_t SeededHash(Key key, uint32_t seed) {
3438  DCHECK(UsesSeed);
3439  return Hash(key);
3440  }
3441  static uint32_t HashForObject(Key key, Object* object) { return 0; }
3442  static uint32_t SeededHashForObject(Key key, uint32_t seed, Object* object) {
3443  DCHECK(UsesSeed);
3444  return HashForObject(key, object);
3445  }
3446  static inline Map* GetMap(Isolate* isolate);
3447 };
3448 
3449 
3450 class HashTableBase : public FixedArray {
3451  public:
3452  // Returns the number of elements in the hash table.
3453  inline int NumberOfElements();
3454 
3455  // Returns the number of deleted elements in the hash table.
3456  inline int NumberOfDeletedElements();
3457 
3458  // Returns the capacity of the hash table.
3459  inline int Capacity();
3460 
3461  // ElementAdded should be called whenever an element is added to a
3462  // hash table.
3463  inline void ElementAdded();
3464 
3465  // ElementRemoved should be called whenever an element is removed from
3466  // a hash table.
3467  inline void ElementRemoved();
3468  inline void ElementsRemoved(int n);
3469 
3470  // Computes the required capacity for a table holding the given
3471  // number of elements. May be more than HashTable::kMaxCapacity.
3472  static inline int ComputeCapacity(int at_least_space_for);
3473 
3474  // Tells whether k is a real key. The hole and undefined are not allowed
3475  // as keys and can be used to indicate missing or deleted elements.
3476  inline bool IsKey(Object* k);
3477  inline bool IsKey(Isolate* isolate, Object* k);
3478 
3479  // Compute the probe offset (quadratic probing).
3480  INLINE(static uint32_t GetProbeOffset(uint32_t n)) {
3481  return (n + n * n) >> 1;
3482  }
3483 
3484  static const int kNumberOfElementsIndex = 0;
3485  static const int kNumberOfDeletedElementsIndex = 1;
3486  static const int kCapacityIndex = 2;
3487  static const int kPrefixStartIndex = 3;
3488 
3489  // Constant used for denoting a absent entry.
3490  static const int kNotFound = -1;
3491 
3492  // Minimum capacity for newly created hash tables.
3493  static const int kMinCapacity = 4;
3494 
3495  protected:
3496  // Update the number of elements in the hash table.
3497  inline void SetNumberOfElements(int nof);
3498 
3499  // Update the number of deleted elements in the hash table.
3500  inline void SetNumberOfDeletedElements(int nod);
3501 
3502  // Returns probe entry.
3503  static uint32_t GetProbe(uint32_t hash, uint32_t number, uint32_t size) {
3504  DCHECK(base::bits::IsPowerOfTwo32(size));
3505  return (hash + GetProbeOffset(number)) & (size - 1);
3506  }
3507 
3508  inline static uint32_t FirstProbe(uint32_t hash, uint32_t size) {
3509  return hash & (size - 1);
3510  }
3511 
3512  inline static uint32_t NextProbe(
3513  uint32_t last, uint32_t number, uint32_t size) {
3514  return (last + number) & (size - 1);
3515  }
3516 };
3517 
3518 
3519 template <typename Derived, typename Shape, typename Key>
3520 class HashTable : public HashTableBase {
3521  public:
3522  typedef Shape ShapeT;
3523 
3524  // Wrapper methods
3525  inline uint32_t Hash(Key key) {
3526  if (Shape::UsesSeed) {
3527  return Shape::SeededHash(key, GetHeap()->HashSeed());
3528  } else {
3529  return Shape::Hash(key);
3530  }
3531  }
3532 
3533  inline uint32_t HashForObject(Key key, Object* object) {
3534  if (Shape::UsesSeed) {
3535  return Shape::SeededHashForObject(key, GetHeap()->HashSeed(), object);
3536  } else {
3537  return Shape::HashForObject(key, object);
3538  }
3539  }
3540 
3541  // Returns a new HashTable object.
3542  MUST_USE_RESULT static Handle<Derived> New(
3543  Isolate* isolate, int at_least_space_for,
3544  MinimumCapacity capacity_option = USE_DEFAULT_MINIMUM_CAPACITY,
3545  PretenureFlag pretenure = NOT_TENURED);
3546 
3547  DECLARE_CAST(HashTable)
3548 
3549  // Garbage collection support.
3550  void IteratePrefix(ObjectVisitor* visitor);
3551  void IterateElements(ObjectVisitor* visitor);
3552 
3553  // Find entry for key otherwise return kNotFound.
3554  inline int FindEntry(Key key);
3555  inline int FindEntry(Isolate* isolate, Key key, int32_t hash);
3556  int FindEntry(Isolate* isolate, Key key);
3557  inline bool Has(Isolate* isolate, Key key);
3558  inline bool Has(Key key);
3559 
3560  // Rehashes the table in-place.
3561  void Rehash(Key key);
3562 
3563  // Returns the key at entry.
3564  Object* KeyAt(int entry) { return get(EntryToIndex(entry) + kEntryKeyIndex); }
3565 
3566  static const int kElementsStartIndex = kPrefixStartIndex + Shape::kPrefixSize;
3567  static const int kEntrySize = Shape::kEntrySize;
3568  STATIC_ASSERT(kEntrySize > 0);
3569  static const int kEntryKeyIndex = 0;
3570  static const int kElementsStartOffset =
3571  kHeaderSize + kElementsStartIndex * kPointerSize;
3572  // Maximal capacity of HashTable. Based on maximal length of underlying
3573  // FixedArray. Staying below kMaxCapacity also ensures that EntryToIndex
3574  // cannot overflow.
3575  static const int kMaxCapacity =
3576  (FixedArray::kMaxLength - kElementsStartIndex) / kEntrySize;
3577 
3578  // Returns the index for an entry (of the key)
3579  static inline int EntryToIndex(int entry) {
3580  return (entry * kEntrySize) + kElementsStartIndex;
3581  }
3582 
3583  protected:
3584  friend class ObjectHashTable;
3585 
3586  // Find the entry at which to insert element with the given key that
3587  // has the given hash value.
3588  uint32_t FindInsertionEntry(uint32_t hash);
3589 
3590  // Attempt to shrink hash table after removal of key.
3591  MUST_USE_RESULT static Handle<Derived> Shrink(Handle<Derived> table, Key key);
3592 
3593  // Ensure enough space for n additional elements.
3594  MUST_USE_RESULT static Handle<Derived> EnsureCapacity(
3595  Handle<Derived> table,
3596  int n,
3597  Key key,
3598  PretenureFlag pretenure = NOT_TENURED);
3599 
3600  // Returns true if this table has sufficient capacity for adding n elements.
3601  bool HasSufficientCapacityToAdd(int number_of_additional_elements);
3602 
3603  // Sets the capacity of the hash table.
3604  void SetCapacity(int capacity) {
3605  // To scale a computed hash code to fit within the hash table, we
3606  // use bit-wise AND with a mask, so the capacity must be positive
3607  // and non-zero.
3608  DCHECK(capacity > 0);
3609  DCHECK(capacity <= kMaxCapacity);
3610  set(kCapacityIndex, Smi::FromInt(capacity));
3611  }
3612 
3613  private:
3614  // Returns _expected_ if one of entries given by the first _probe_ probes is
3615  // equal to _expected_. Otherwise, returns the entry given by the probe
3616  // number _probe_.
3617  uint32_t EntryForProbe(Key key, Object* k, int probe, uint32_t expected);
3618 
3619  void Swap(uint32_t entry1, uint32_t entry2, WriteBarrierMode mode);
3620 
3621  // Rehashes this hash-table into the new table.
3622  void Rehash(Handle<Derived> new_table, Key key);
3623 };
3624

3626 // HashTableKey is an abstract superclass for virtual key behavior.
3627 class HashTableKey {
3628  public:
3629  // Returns whether the other object matches this key.
3630  virtual bool IsMatch(Object* other) = 0;
3631  // Returns the hash value for this key.
3632  virtual uint32_t Hash() = 0;
3633  // Returns the hash value for object.
3634  virtual uint32_t HashForObject(Object* key) = 0;
3635  // Returns the key object for storing into the hash table.
3636  MUST_USE_RESULT virtual Handle<Object> AsHandle(Isolate* isolate) = 0;
3637  // Required.
3638  virtual ~HashTableKey() {}
3639 };

3818 #endif

3824  Handle<Object> key,
3825  Handle<Object> value);

3827  Handle<Object> key,
3828  Handle<Object> value,
3829  PropertyDetails details);

3832  Key key, Handle<Object> value,
3833  PropertyDetails details,
3834  int* entry_out = nullptr);

3892  return false;

4161 
4162  inline bool Has(Isolate* isolate, Handle<Object> key, int32_t hash);
4163  inline bool Has(Isolate* isolate, Handle<Object> key);
4164 
4165  DECLARE_CAST(ObjectHashSet)
4166 };
4167 
4168 // OrderedHashTable is a HashTable with Object keys that preserves
4169 // insertion order. There are Map and Set interfaces (OrderedHashMap
4170 // and OrderedHashTable, below). It is meant to be used by JSMap/JSSet.
4171 //
4172 // Only Object* keys are supported, with Object::SameValueZero() used as the
4173 // equality operator and Object::GetHash() for the hash function.
4174 //
4175 // Based on the "Deterministic Hash Table" as described by Jason Orendorff at
4176 // https://wiki.mozilla.org/User:Jorend/Deterministic_hash_tables
4177 // Originally attributed to Tyler Close.
4178 //
4179 // Memory layout:
4180 // [0]: bucket count
4181 // [1]: element count
4182 // [2]: deleted element count
4183 // [3..(3 + NumberOfBuckets() - 1)]: "hash table", where each item is an
4184 // offset into the data table (see below) where the
4185 // first item in this bucket is stored.
4186 // [3 + NumberOfBuckets()..length]: "data table", an array of length
4187 // Capacity() * kEntrySize, where the first entrysize
4188 // items are handled by the derived class and the
4189 // item at kChainOffset is another entry into the
4190 // data table indicating the next entry in this hash
4191 // bucket.
4192 //
4193 // When we transition the table to a new version we obsolete it and reuse parts
4194 // of the memory to store information how to transition an iterator to the new
4195 // table:
4196 //
4197 // Memory layout for obsolete table:
4198 // [0]: bucket count
4199 // [1]: Next newer table
4200 // [2]: Number of removed holes or -1 when the table was cleared.
4201 // [3..(3 + NumberOfRemovedHoles() - 1)]: The indexes of the removed holes.
4202 // [3 + NumberOfRemovedHoles()..length]: Not used
4203 //
4204 template<class Derived, class Iterator, int entrysize>
4205 class OrderedHashTable: public FixedArray {
4206  public:
4207  // Returns an OrderedHashTable with a capacity of at least |capacity|.
4208  static Handle<Derived> Allocate(
4209  Isolate* isolate, int capacity, PretenureFlag pretenure = NOT_TENURED);
4210 
4211  // Returns an OrderedHashTable (possibly |table|) with enough space
4212  // to add at least one new element.
4213  static Handle<Derived> EnsureGrowable(Handle<Derived> table);
4214 
4215  // Returns an OrderedHashTable (possibly |table|) that's shrunken
4216  // if possible.
4217  static Handle<Derived> Shrink(Handle<Derived> table);
4218 
4219  // Returns a new empty OrderedHashTable and records the clearing so that
4220  // existing iterators can be updated.
4221  static Handle<Derived> Clear(Handle<Derived> table);
4222 
4223  // Returns a true if the OrderedHashTable contains the key
4224  static bool HasKey(Handle<Derived> table, Handle<Object> key);
4225 
4226  int NumberOfElements() {
4227  return Smi::cast(get(kNumberOfElementsIndex))->value();
4228  }
4229 
4230  int NumberOfDeletedElements() {
4231  return Smi::cast(get(kNumberOfDeletedElementsIndex))->value();
4232  }
4233 
4234  // Returns the number of contiguous entries in the data table, starting at 0,
4235  // that either are real entries or have been deleted.
4236  int UsedCapacity() { return NumberOfElements() + NumberOfDeletedElements(); }
4237 
4238  int NumberOfBuckets() {
4239  return Smi::cast(get(kNumberOfBucketsIndex))->value();
4240  }
4241 
4242  // Returns an index into |this| for the given entry.
4243  int EntryToIndex(int entry) {
4244  return kHashTableStartIndex + NumberOfBuckets() + (entry * kEntrySize);
4245  }
4246 
4247  int HashToBucket(int hash) { return hash & (NumberOfBuckets() - 1); }
4248 
4249  int HashToEntry(int hash) {
4250  int bucket = HashToBucket(hash);
4251  Object* entry = this->get(kHashTableStartIndex + bucket);
4252  return Smi::cast(entry)->value();
4253  }
4254 
4255  int KeyToFirstEntry(Isolate* isolate, Object* key) {
4256  Object* hash = key->GetHash();
4257  // If the object does not have an identity hash, it was never used as a key
4258  if (hash->IsUndefined(isolate)) return kNotFound;
4259  return HashToEntry(Smi::cast(hash)->value());
4260  }
4261 
4262  int NextChainEntry(int entry) {
4263  Object* next_entry = get(EntryToIndex(entry) + kChainOffset);
4264  return Smi::cast(next_entry)->value();
4265  }
4266 
4267  // use KeyAt(i)->IsTheHole(isolate) to determine if this is a deleted entry.
4268  Object* KeyAt(int entry) {
4269  DCHECK_LT(entry, this->UsedCapacity());
4270  return get(EntryToIndex(entry));
4271  }
4272 
4273  bool IsObsolete() {
4274  return !get(kNextTableIndex)->IsSmi();
4275  }
4276 
4277  // The next newer table. This is only valid if the table is obsolete.
4278  Derived* NextTable() {
4279  return Derived::cast(get(kNextTableIndex));
4280  }
4281 
4282  // When the table is obsolete we store the indexes of the removed holes.
4283  int RemovedIndexAt(int index) {
4284  return Smi::cast(get(kRemovedHolesIndex + index))->value();
4285  }
4286 
4287  static const int kNotFound = -1;
4288  static const int kMinCapacity = 4;
4289 
4290  static const int kNumberOfBucketsIndex = 0;
4291  static const int kNumberOfElementsIndex = kNumberOfBucketsIndex + 1;
4292  static const int kNumberOfDeletedElementsIndex = kNumberOfElementsIndex + 1;
4293  static const int kHashTableStartIndex = kNumberOfDeletedElementsIndex + 1;
4294  static const int kNextTableIndex = kNumberOfElementsIndex;
4295 
4296  static const int kNumberOfBucketsOffset =
4297  kHeaderSize + kNumberOfBucketsIndex * kPointerSize;
4298  static const int kNumberOfElementsOffset =
4299  kHeaderSize + kNumberOfElementsIndex * kPointerSize;
4300  static const int kNumberOfDeletedElementsOffset =
4301  kHeaderSize + kNumberOfDeletedElementsIndex * kPointerSize;
4302  static const int kHashTableStartOffset =
4303  kHeaderSize + kHashTableStartIndex * kPointerSize;
4304  static const int kNextTableOffset =
4305  kHeaderSize + kNextTableIndex * kPointerSize;
4306 
4307  static const int kEntrySize = entrysize + 1;
4308  static const int kChainOffset = entrysize;
4309 
4310  static const int kLoadFactor = 2;
4311 
4312  // NumberOfDeletedElements is set to kClearedTableSentinel when
4313  // the table is cleared, which allows iterator transitions to
4314  // optimize that case.
4315  static const int kClearedTableSentinel = -1;
4316 
4317  protected:
4318  static Handle<Derived> Rehash(Handle<Derived> table, int new_capacity);
4319 
4320  void SetNumberOfBuckets(int num) {
4321  set(kNumberOfBucketsIndex, Smi::FromInt(num));
4322  }
4323 
4324  void SetNumberOfElements(int num) {
4325  set(kNumberOfElementsIndex, Smi::FromInt(num));
4326  }
4327 
4328  void SetNumberOfDeletedElements(int num) {
4329  set(kNumberOfDeletedElementsIndex, Smi::FromInt(num));
4330  }
4331 
4332  // Returns the number elements that can fit into the allocated buffer.
4333  int Capacity() {
4334  return NumberOfBuckets() * kLoadFactor;
4335  }
4336 
4337  void SetNextTable(Derived* next_table) {
4338  set(kNextTableIndex, next_table);
4339  }
4340 
4341  void SetRemovedIndexAt(int index, int removed_index) {
4342  return set(kRemovedHolesIndex + index, Smi::FromInt(removed_index));
4343  }
4344 
4345  static const int kRemovedHolesIndex = kHashTableStartIndex;
4346 
4347  static const int kMaxCapacity =
4348  (FixedArray::kMaxLength - kHashTableStartIndex)
4349  / (1 + (kEntrySize * kLoadFactor));
4350 };
4351

4387  static inline uint32_t HashForObject(Handle<Object> key, Object* object);

4394 // WeakHashTable maps keys that are arbitrary heap objects to heap object
4395 // values. The table wraps the keys in weak cells and store values directly.
4396 // Thus it references keys weakly and values strongly.
4397 class WeakHashTable: public HashTable<WeakHashTable,
4398  WeakHashTableShape<2>,
4399  Handle<Object> > {

4401  WeakHashTable, WeakHashTableShape<2>, Handle<Object> > DerivedHashTable;
4402  public:

4405  // Looks up the value associated with the given key. The hole value is
4406  // returned in case the key is not present.
4407  Object* Lookup(Handle<HeapObject> key);
4408 
4409  // Adds (or overwrites) the value associated with the given key. Mapping a
4410  // key to the hole value causes removal of the whole entry.
4411  MUST_USE_RESULT static Handle<WeakHashTable> Put(Handle<WeakHashTable> table,
4412  Handle<HeapObject> key,
4413  Handle<HeapObject> value);
4414 
4415  static Handle<FixedArray> GetValues(Handle<WeakHashTable> table);
4416 
4417  private:
4418  friend class MarkCompactCollector;
4419 
4420  void AddEntry(int entry, Handle<WeakCell> key, Handle<HeapObject> value);
4421 
4422  // Returns the index to the value of an entry.
4423  static inline int EntryToValueIndex(int entry) {

4425  }

4429 // ScopeInfo represents information about different scopes of a source
4430 // program and the allocation of the scope's variables. Scope information
4431 // is stored in a compressed form in ScopeInfo objects and is used
4432 // at runtime (stack dumps, deoptimization, etc.).
4433 
4434 // This object provides quick access to scope info details for runtime
4435 // routines.
4436 class ScopeInfo : public FixedArray {
4437  public:
4438  DECLARE_CAST(ScopeInfo)
4439 
4440  // Return the type of this scope.
4441  ScopeType scope_type();
4442 
4443  // Does this scope call eval?
4444  bool CallsEval();
4445 
4446  // Return the language mode of this scope.
4447  LanguageMode language_mode();
4448 
4449  // True if this scope is a (var) declaration scope.
4450  bool is_declaration_scope();
4451 
4452  // Does this scope make a sloppy eval call?
4453  bool CallsSloppyEval() { return CallsEval() && is_sloppy(language_mode()); }
4454 
4455  // Return the total number of locals allocated on the stack and in the
4456  // context. This includes the parameters that are allocated in the context.
4457  int LocalCount();
4458 
4459  // Return the number of stack slots for code. This number consists of two
4460  // parts:
4461  // 1. One stack slot per stack allocated local.
4462  // 2. One stack slot for the function name if it is stack allocated.
4463  int StackSlotCount();
4464 
4465  // Return the number of context slots for code if a context is allocated. This
4466  // number consists of three parts:
4467  // 1. Size of fixed header for every context: Context::MIN_CONTEXT_SLOTS
4468  // 2. One context slot per context allocated local.
4469  // 3. One context slot for the function name if it is context allocated.
4470  // Parameters allocated in the context count as context allocated locals. If
4471  // no contexts are allocated for this scope ContextLength returns 0.
4472  int ContextLength();
4473 
4474  // Does this scope declare a "this" binding?

4476

4478  // or context-allocated?
4479  bool HasAllocatedReceiver();
4480 
4481  // Does this scope declare a "new.target" binding?
4482  bool HasNewTarget();
4483

4485  bool HasFunctionName();
4486

4488  bool HasHeapAllocatedLocals();

4495

4497  inline bool IsAsmFunction();
4498

4500 
4501  // Return the function_name if present.
4502  String* FunctionName();

4511

4513  String* StackLocalName(int var);
4514 
4515  // Return the name of the given stack local.
4516  int StackLocalIndex(int var);
4517 
4518  // Return the name of the given context local.
4519  String* ContextLocalName(int var);
4520

4522  VariableMode ContextLocalMode(int var);
4523

4531  // exposed to the user in a debugger.

4533 
4534  // Lookup support for serialized scope info. Returns the
4535  // the stack slot index for a given slot name if the slot is
4536  // present; otherwise returns a value < 0. The name must be an internalized
4537  // string.
4538  int StackSlotIndex(String* name);
4539

4541  // index for a given slot name if the slot is present; otherwise
4542  // returns a value < 0. The name must be an internalized string.
4543  // If the slot is present and mode != NULL, sets *mode to the corresponding
4544  // mode for that variable.
4545  static int ContextSlotIndex(Handle<ScopeInfo> scope_info, Handle<String> name,
4546  VariableMode* mode, InitializationFlag* init_flag,

4554

4557

4560  // otherwise returns a value < 0. The name must be an internalized string.
4561  int ParameterIndex(String* name);
4562

4583  // being a debug-evaluate scope.

4596  Isolate* isolate, MaybeHandle<ScopeInfo> outer_scope);
4597  static Handle<ScopeInfo> CreateGlobalThisBinding(Isolate* isolate);
4598 
4599  // Serializes empty scope info.
4600  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE static ScopeInfo* Empty(Isolate* isolate);
4601 
4602 #ifdef DEBUG
4603  void Print();
4604 #endif
4605 
4606  // The layout of the static part of a ScopeInfo is as follows. Each entry is
4607  // numeric and occupies one array slot.
4608 // 1. A set of properties of the scope.
4609 // 2. The number of parameters. For non-function scopes this is 0.
4610 // 3. The number of non-parameter variables allocated on the stack.
4611 // 4. The number of non-parameter and parameter variables allocated in the
4612 // context.
4613 #define FOR_EACH_SCOPE_INFO_NUMERIC_FIELD(V) \
4614  V(Flags) \
4615  V(ParameterCount) \
4616  V(StackLocalCount) \
4617  V(ContextLocalCount)
4618 
4619 #define FIELD_ACCESSORS(name) \
4620  inline void Set##name(int value); \
4621  inline int name();
4622  FOR_EACH_SCOPE_INFO_NUMERIC_FIELD(FIELD_ACCESSORS)
4623 #undef FIELD_ACCESSORS
4624 
4625  enum {
4626 #define DECL_INDEX(name) k##name,
4627  FOR_EACH_SCOPE_INFO_NUMERIC_FIELD(DECL_INDEX)
4628 #undef DECL_INDEX
4629  kVariablePartIndex
4630  };
4631 
4632  private:
4633  // The layout of the variable part of a ScopeInfo is as follows:
4634  // 1. ParameterNames:
4635  // This part stores the names of the parameters for function scopes. One
4636  // slot is used per parameter, so in total this part occupies
4637  // ParameterCount() slots in the array. For other scopes than function
4638  // scopes ParameterCount() is 0.
4639  // 2. StackLocalFirstSlot:
4640  // Index of a first stack slot for stack local. Stack locals belonging to
4641  // this scope are located on a stack at slots starting from this index.
4642  // 3. StackLocalNames:
4643  // Contains the names of local variables that are allocated on the stack,
4644  // in increasing order of the stack slot index. First local variable has a
4645  // stack slot index defined in StackLocalFirstSlot (point 2 above).
4646  // One slot is used per stack local, so in total this part occupies
4647  // StackLocalCount() slots in the array.
4648  // 4. ContextLocalNames:
4649  // Contains the names of local variables and parameters that are allocated
4650  // in the context. They are stored in increasing order of the context slot
4651  // index starting with Context::MIN_CONTEXT_SLOTS. One slot is used per
4652  // context local, so in total this part occupies ContextLocalCount() slots
4653  // in the array.
4654  // 5. ContextLocalInfos:
4655  // Contains the variable modes and initialization flags corresponding to
4656  // the context locals in ContextLocalNames. One slot is used per
4657  // context local, so in total this part occupies ContextLocalCount()
4658  // slots in the array.
4659  // 6. ReceiverInfo:
4660  // If the scope binds a "this" value, one slot is reserved to hold the
4661  // context or stack slot index for the variable.
4662  // 7. FunctionNameInfo:
4663  // If the scope belongs to a named function expression this part contains
4664  // information about the function variable. It always occupies two array
4665  // slots: a. The name of the function variable.
4666  // b. The context or stack slot index for the variable.
4667  // 8. OuterScopeInfoIndex:
4668  // The outer scope's ScopeInfo or the hole if there's none.
4669  // 9. ModuleInfo, ModuleVariableCount, and ModuleVariables:
4670  // For a module scope, this part contains the ModuleInfo, the number of
4671  // MODULE-allocated variables, and the metadata of those variables. For
4672  // non-module scopes it is empty.
4673  int ParameterNamesIndex();
4674  int StackLocalFirstSlotIndex();
4675  int StackLocalNamesIndex();
4676  int ContextLocalNamesIndex();
4677  int ContextLocalInfosIndex();
4678  int ReceiverInfoIndex();
4679  int FunctionNameInfoIndex();
4680  int OuterScopeInfoIndex();
4681  int ModuleInfoIndex();
4682  int ModuleVariableCountIndex();
4683  int ModuleVariablesIndex();
4684 
4685  int Lookup(Handle<String> name, int start, int end, VariableMode* mode,
4686  VariableLocation* location, InitializationFlag* init_flag,
4687  MaybeAssignedFlag* maybe_assigned_flag);
4688 
4689  // Get metadata of i-th MODULE-allocated variable, where 0 <= i <
4690  // ModuleVariableCount. The metadata is returned via out-arguments, which may
4691  // be nullptr if the corresponding information is not requested
4692  void ModuleVariable(int i, String** name, int* index,
4693  VariableMode* mode = nullptr,
4694  InitializationFlag* init_flag = nullptr,
4695  MaybeAssignedFlag* maybe_assigned_flag = nullptr);
4696 
4697  // Used for the function name variable for named function expressions, and for
4698  // the receiver.
4699  enum VariableAllocationInfo { NONE, STACK, CONTEXT, UNUSED };
4700 
4701  // Properties of scopes.
4702  class ScopeTypeField : public BitField<ScopeType, 0, 4> {};
4703  class CallsEvalField : public BitField<bool, ScopeTypeField::kNext, 1> {};
4704  STATIC_ASSERT(LANGUAGE_END == 2);
4705  class LanguageModeField
4706  : public BitField<LanguageMode, CallsEvalField::kNext, 1> {};
4707  class DeclarationScopeField
4708  : public BitField<bool, LanguageModeField::kNext, 1> {};
4709  class ReceiverVariableField
4710  : public BitField<VariableAllocationInfo, DeclarationScopeField::kNext,
4711  2> {};
4712  class HasNewTargetField
4713  : public BitField<bool, ReceiverVariableField::kNext, 1> {};
4714  class FunctionVariableField
4715  : public BitField<VariableAllocationInfo, HasNewTargetField::kNext, 2> {};
4716  class AsmModuleField
4717  : public BitField<bool, FunctionVariableField::kNext, 1> {};
4718  class AsmFunctionField : public BitField<bool, AsmModuleField::kNext, 1> {};
4719  class HasSimpleParametersField
4720  : public BitField<bool, AsmFunctionField::kNext, 1> {};
4721  class FunctionKindField
4722  : public BitField<FunctionKind, HasSimpleParametersField::kNext, 10> {};
4723  class HasOuterScopeInfoField
4724  : public BitField<bool, FunctionKindField::kNext, 1> {};
4725  class IsDebugEvaluateScopeField
4726  : public BitField<bool, HasOuterScopeInfoField::kNext, 1> {};
4727 
4728  // Properties of variables.
4729  class VariableModeField : public BitField<VariableMode, 0, 3> {};
4730  class InitFlagField : public BitField<InitializationFlag, 3, 1> {};
4731  class MaybeAssignedFlagField : public BitField<MaybeAssignedFlag, 4, 1> {};
4732 
4733  friend class ScopeIterator;
4734 };

4765 // ModuleInfo is to ModuleDescriptor what ScopeInfo is to Scope.
4766 class ModuleInfo : public FixedArray {
4767  public:
4768  DECLARE_CAST(ModuleInfo)

4825 
4826 // HandlerTable is a fixed array containing entries for exception handlers in
4827 // the code object it is associated with. The tables comes in two flavors:
4828 // 1) Based on ranges: Used for unoptimized code. Contains one entry per
4829 // exception handler and a range representing the try-block covered by that
4830 // handler. Layout looks as follows:
4831 // [ range-start , range-end , handler-offset , handler-data ]
4832 // 2) Based on return addresses: Used for turbofanned code. Contains one entry
4833 // per call-site that could throw an exception. Layout looks as follows:
4834 // [ return-address-offset , handler-offset ]
4835 class HandlerTable : public FixedArray {
4836  public:
4837  // Conservative prediction whether a given handler will locally catch an
4838  // exception or cause a re-throw to outside the code boundary. Since this is
4839  // undecidable it is merely an approximation (e.g. useful for debugger).
4840  enum CatchPrediction {
4841  UNCAUGHT, // The handler will (likely) rethrow the exception.
4842  CAUGHT, // The exception will be caught by the handler.
4843  PROMISE, // The exception will be caught and cause a promise rejection.
4844  DESUGARING, // The exception will be caught, but both the exception and the
4845  // catching are part of a desugaring and should therefore not
4846  // be visible to the user (we won't notify the debugger of such
4847  // exceptions).
4848  ASYNC_AWAIT, // The exception will be caught and cause a promise rejection
4849  // in the desugaring of an async function, so special
4850  // async/await handling in the debugger can take place.
4851  };
4852 
4853  // Getters for handler table based on ranges.
4854  inline int GetRangeStart(int index) const;
4855  inline int GetRangeEnd(int index) const;
4856  inline int GetRangeHandler(int index) const;
4857  inline int GetRangeData(int index) const;
4858 
4859  // Setters for handler table based on ranges.
4860  inline void SetRangeStart(int index, int value);
4861  inline void SetRangeEnd(int index, int value);
4862  inline void SetRangeHandler(int index, int offset, CatchPrediction pred);
4863  inline void SetRangeData(int index, int value);
4864 
4865  // Setters for handler table based on return addresses.
4866  inline void SetReturnOffset(int index, int value);
4867  inline void SetReturnHandler(int index, int offset);
4868 
4869  // Lookup handler in a table based on ranges.
4870  int LookupRange(int pc_offset, int* data, CatchPrediction* prediction);
4871 
4872  // Lookup handler in a table based on return addresses.
4873  int LookupReturn(int pc_offset);
4874 
4875  // Returns the number of entries in the table.
4876  inline int NumberOfRangeEntries() const;
4877 
4878  // Returns the required length of the underlying fixed array.
4879  static int LengthForRange(int entries) { return entries * kRangeEntrySize; }
4880  static int LengthForReturn(int entries) { return entries * kReturnEntrySize; }
4881 
4882  DECLARE_CAST(HandlerTable)
4883 
4884 #ifdef ENABLE_DISASSEMBLER
4885  void HandlerTableRangePrint(std::ostream& os); // NOLINT
4886  void HandlerTableReturnPrint(std::ostream& os); // NOLINT
4887 #endif
4888 
4889  private:
4890  // Layout description for handler table based on ranges.
4891  static const int kRangeStartIndex = 0;
4892  static const int kRangeEndIndex = 1;
4893  static const int kRangeHandlerIndex = 2;
4894  static const int kRangeDataIndex = 3;
4895  static const int kRangeEntrySize = 4;
4896 
4897  // Layout description for handler table based on return addresses.
4898  static const int kReturnOffsetIndex = 0;
4899  static const int kReturnHandlerIndex = 1;
4900  static const int kReturnEntrySize = 2;
4901 
4902  // Encoding of the {handler} field.
4903  class HandlerPredictionField : public BitField<CatchPrediction, 0, 3> {};
4904  class HandlerOffsetField : public BitField<int, 3, 29> {};
4905 };

4907 // ByteArray represents fixed sized byte arrays. Used for the relocation info
4908 // that is attached to code objects.
4909 class ByteArray: public FixedArrayBase {
4910  public:
4911  inline int Size();
4912 
4913  // Setter and getter.
4914  inline byte get(int index);
4915  inline void set(int index, byte value);
4916 
4917  // Copy in / copy out whole byte slices.
4918  inline void copy_out(int index, byte* buffer, int length);
4919  inline void copy_in(int index, const byte* buffer, int length);
4920 
4921  // Treat contents as an int array.
4922  inline int get_int(int index);
4923  inline void set_int(int index, int value);
4924 
4925  static int SizeFor(int length) {
4926  return OBJECT_POINTER_ALIGN(kHeaderSize + length);
4927  }
4928  // We use byte arrays for free blocks in the heap. Given a desired size in
4929  // bytes that is a multiple of the word size and big enough to hold a byte
4930  // array, this function returns the number of elements a byte array should
4931  // have.
4932  static int LengthFor(int size_in_bytes) {
4933  DCHECK(IsAligned(size_in_bytes, kPointerSize));
4934  DCHECK(size_in_bytes >= kHeaderSize);
4935  return size_in_bytes - kHeaderSize;
4936  }
4937 
4938  // Returns data start address.
4939  inline Address GetDataStartAddress();
4940 
4941  // Returns a pointer to the ByteArray object for a given data start address.
4942  static inline ByteArray* FromDataStartAddress(Address address);
4943 
4944  DECLARE_CAST(ByteArray)
4945 
4946  // Dispatched behavior.
4947  inline int ByteArraySize();
4948  DECLARE_PRINTER(ByteArray)
4949  DECLARE_VERIFIER(ByteArray)
4950 
4951  // Layout description.
4952  static const int kAlignedSize = OBJECT_POINTER_ALIGN(kHeaderSize);
4953 
4954  // Maximal memory consumption for a single ByteArray.
4955  static const int kMaxSize = 512 * MB;
4956  // Maximal length of a single ByteArray.
4957  static const int kMaxLength = kMaxSize - kHeaderSize;
4958 
4959  private:
4960  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(ByteArray);
4961 };

5061 // FreeSpace are fixed-size free memory blocks used by the heap and GC.
5062 // They look like heap objects (are heap object tagged and have a map) so that
5063 // the heap remains iterable. They have a size and a next pointer.

5065 // in the free list.

5074 
5075  inline int Size();
5076 
5077  // Accessors for the next field.

5080 
5081  inline static FreeSpace* cast(HeapObject* obj);
5082 
5083  // Dispatched behavior.
5084  DECLARE_PRINTER(FreeSpace)
5085  DECLARE_VERIFIER(FreeSpace)
5086 
5087  // Layout description.
5088  // Size is smi tagged when it is stored.
5089  static const int kSizeOffset = HeapObject::kHeaderSize;
5090  static const int kNextOffset = POINTER_SIZE_ALIGN(kSizeOffset + kPointerSize);
5091  static const int kSize = kNextOffset + kPointerSize;
5092 
5093  private:

5095 };

5196 // DeoptimizationInputData is a fixed array used to hold the deoptimization

5599  class FindAndReplacePattern;
5600  // For each (map-to-find, object-to-replace) pair in the pattern, this
5601  // function replaces the corresponding placeholder in the code with the
5602  // object-to-replace. The function assumes that pairs in the pattern come in
5603  // the same order as the placeholders in the code.
5604  // If the placeholder is a weak cell, then the value of weak cell is matched
5605  // against the map-to-find.
5606  void FindAndReplace(const FindAndReplacePattern& pattern);
5607 
5608  // The entire code object including its header is copied verbatim to the
5609  // snapshot so that it can be written in one, fast, memcpy during
5610  // deserialization. The deserializer will overwrite some pointers, rather
5611  // like a runtime linker, but the random allocation addresses used in the
5612  // mksnapshot process would still be present in the unlinked snapshot data,
5613  // which would make snapshot production non-reproducible. This method wipes
5614  // out the to-be-overwritten header data for reproducible snapshots.
5615  inline void WipeOutHeader();

5654  // [has_unwinding_info]: Whether this code object has unwinding information.
5655  // If it doesn't, unwinding_information_start() will point to invalid data.
5656  //
5657  // The body of all code objects has the following layout.
5658  //
5659  // +--------------------------+ <-- instruction_start()
5660  // | instructions |
5661  // | ... |
5662  // +--------------------------+
5663  // | relocation info |
5664  // | ... |
5665  // +--------------------------+ <-- instruction_end()
5666  //
5667  // If has_unwinding_info() is false, instruction_end() points to the first
5668  // memory location after the end of the code object. Otherwise, the body
5669  // continues as follows:
5670  //
5671  // +--------------------------+
5672  // | padding to the next |
5673  // | 8-byte aligned address |
5674  // +--------------------------+ <-- instruction_end()
5675  // | [unwinding_info_size] |
5676  // | as uint64_t |
5677  // +--------------------------+ <-- unwinding_info_start()
5678  // | unwinding info |
5679  // | ... |
5680  // +--------------------------+ <-- unwinding_info_end()
5681  //
5682  // and unwinding_info_end() points to the first memory location after the end
5683  // of the code object.
5684  //
5685  DECL_BOOLEAN_ACCESSORS(has_unwinding_info)
5686 
5687  // [unwinding_info_size]: Size of the unwinding information.
5688  inline int unwinding_info_size() const;
5689  inline void set_unwinding_info_size(int value);
5690 
5691  // Returns the address of the unwinding information, if any.
5692  inline byte* unwinding_info_start();
5693 
5694  // Returns the address right after the end of the unwinding information.
5695  inline byte* unwinding_info_end();

5828  // Byte offsets within kKindSpecificFlags1Offset.
5829  static const int kFullCodeFlags = kKindSpecificFlags1Offset;
5830  class FullCodeFlagsHasDeoptimizationSupportField:
5831  public BitField<bool, 0, 1> {}; // NOLINT
5832  class FullCodeFlagsHasDebugBreakSlotsField: public BitField<bool, 1, 1> {};
5833  class FullCodeFlagsHasRelocInfoForSerialization
5834  : public BitField<bool, 2, 1> {};
5835  // Bit 3 in this bitfield is unused.
5836  class ProfilerTicksField : public BitField<int, 4, 28> {};
5837 
5838  // Flags layout. BitField<type, shift, size>.
5839  class HasUnwindingInfoField : public BitField<bool, 0, 1> {};
5840  class CacheHolderField
5841  : public BitField<CacheHolderFlag, HasUnwindingInfoField::kNext, 2> {};
5842  class KindField : public BitField<Kind, CacheHolderField::kNext, 5> {};
5843  STATIC_ASSERT(NUMBER_OF_KINDS <= KindField::kMax);
5844  class ExtraICStateField
5845  : public BitField<ExtraICState, KindField::kNext,
5846  PlatformSmiTagging::kSmiValueSize - KindField::kNext> {
5847  };
5848 
5849  // KindSpecificFlags1 layout (STUB, BUILTIN and OPTIMIZED_FUNCTION)
5850  static const int kStackSlotsFirstBit = 0;
5851  static const int kStackSlotsBitCount = 24;
5852  static const int kMarkedForDeoptimizationBit =
5853  kStackSlotsFirstBit + kStackSlotsBitCount;
5854  static const int kIsTurbofannedBit = kMarkedForDeoptimizationBit + 1;
5855  static const int kCanHaveWeakObjects = kIsTurbofannedBit + 1;
5856  // Could be moved to overlap previous bits when we need more space.
5857  static const int kIsConstructStub = kCanHaveWeakObjects + 1;
5858 
5859  STATIC_ASSERT(kStackSlotsFirstBit + kStackSlotsBitCount <= 32);
5860  STATIC_ASSERT(kIsConstructStub + 1 <= 32);
5861 
5862  class StackSlotsField: public BitField<int,
5863  kStackSlotsFirstBit, kStackSlotsBitCount> {}; // NOLINT
5864  class MarkedForDeoptimizationField
5865  : public BitField<bool, kMarkedForDeoptimizationBit, 1> {}; // NOLINT
5866  class IsTurbofannedField : public BitField<bool, kIsTurbofannedBit, 1> {
5867  }; // NOLINT
5868  class CanHaveWeakObjectsField
5869  : public BitField<bool, kCanHaveWeakObjects, 1> {}; // NOLINT
5870  class IsConstructStubField : public BitField<bool, kIsConstructStub, 1> {
5871  }; // NOLINT
5872 
5873  // KindSpecificFlags2 layout (ALL)
5874  static const int kIsCrankshaftedBit = 0;
5875  class IsCrankshaftedField: public BitField<bool,
5876  kIsCrankshaftedBit, 1> {}; // NOLINT
5877 
5878  // KindSpecificFlags2 layout (STUB and OPTIMIZED_FUNCTION)
5879  static const int kSafepointTableOffsetFirstBit = kIsCrankshaftedBit + 1;
5880  static const int kSafepointTableOffsetBitCount = 30;
5881 
5882  STATIC_ASSERT(kSafepointTableOffsetFirstBit +
5883  kSafepointTableOffsetBitCount <= 32);
5884  STATIC_ASSERT(1 + kSafepointTableOffsetBitCount <= 32);
5885 
5886  class SafepointTableOffsetField: public BitField<int,
5887  kSafepointTableOffsetFirstBit,
5888  kSafepointTableOffsetBitCount> {}; // NOLINT
5889 
5890  // KindSpecificFlags2 layout (FUNCTION)
5891  class BackEdgeTableOffsetField: public BitField<int,
5892  kIsCrankshaftedBit + 1, 27> {}; // NOLINT
5893  class AllowOSRAtLoopNestingLevelField: public BitField<int,
5894  kIsCrankshaftedBit + 1 + 27, 4> {}; // NOLINT
5895 
5896  static const int kArgumentsBits = 16;
5897  static const int kMaxArguments = (1 << kArgumentsBits) - 1;
5898 
5899  // This constant should be encodable in an ARM instruction.
5900  static const int kFlagsNotUsedInLookup = CacheHolderField::kMask;
5901 
5902  private:
5903  friend class RelocIterator;
5904  friend class Deoptimizer; // For FindCodeAgeSequence.
5905

5917  MarkingParity parity);

5978  kMaxLoopNestingMarker);

5980 
5981 // Dependent code is a singly linked list of fixed arrays. Each array contains
5982 // code objects in weak cells for one dependent group. The suffix of the array
5983 // can be filled with the undefined value if the number of codes is less than
5984 // the length of the array.
5985 //
5986 // +------+-----------------+--------+--------+-----+--------+-----------+-----+
5987 // | next | count & group 1 | code 1 | code 2 | ... | code n | undefined | ... |
5988 // +------+-----------------+--------+--------+-----+--------+-----------+-----+
5989 // |
5990 // V
5991 // +------+-----------------+--------+--------+-----+--------+-----------+-----+
5992 // | next | count & group 2 | code 1 | code 2 | ... | code m | undefined | ... |
5993 // +------+-----------------+--------+--------+-----+--------+-----------+-----+
5994 // |
5995 // V
5996 // empty_fixed_array()
5997 //
5998 // The list of fixed arrays is ordered by dependency groups.
5999 
6000 class DependentCode: public FixedArray {
6001  public:
6002  enum DependencyGroup {
6003  // Group of code that weakly embed this map and depend on being
6004  // deoptimized when the map is garbage collected.
6005  kWeakCodeGroup,
6006  // Group of code that embed a transition to this map, and depend on being
6007  // deoptimized when the transition is replaced by a new version.
6008  kTransitionGroup,
6009  // Group of code that omit run-time prototype checks for prototypes
6010  // described by this map. The group is deoptimized whenever an object
6011  // described by this map changes shape (and transitions to a new map),
6012  // possibly invalidating the assumptions embedded in the code.
6013  kPrototypeCheckGroup,
6014  // Group of code that depends on global property values in property cells
6015  // not being changed.
6016  kPropertyCellChangedGroup,
6017  // Group of code that omit run-time checks for field(s) introduced by
6018  // this map, i.e. for the field type.
6019  kFieldOwnerGroup,
6020  // Group of code that omit run-time type checks for initial maps of
6021  // constructors.
6022  kInitialMapChangedGroup,
6023  // Group of code that depends on tenuring information in AllocationSites
6024  // not being changed.
6025  kAllocationSiteTenuringChangedGroup,
6026  // Group of code that depends on element transition information in
6027  // AllocationSites not being changed.
6028  kAllocationSiteTransitionChangedGroup
6029  };
6030 
6031  static const int kGroupCount = kAllocationSiteTransitionChangedGroup + 1;
6032  static const int kNextLinkIndex = 0;
6033  static const int kFlagsIndex = 1;
6034  static const int kCodesStartIndex = 2;
6035 
6036  bool Contains(DependencyGroup group, WeakCell* code_cell);
6037  bool IsEmpty(DependencyGroup group);
6038 
6039  static Handle<DependentCode> InsertCompilationDependencies(
6040  Handle<DependentCode> entries, DependencyGroup group,
6041  Handle<Foreign> info);
6042 
6043  static Handle<DependentCode> InsertWeakCode(Handle<DependentCode> entries,
6044  DependencyGroup group,
6045  Handle<WeakCell> code_cell);
6046 
6047  void UpdateToFinishedCode(DependencyGroup group, Foreign* info,
6048  WeakCell* code_cell);
6049 
6050  void RemoveCompilationDependencies(DependentCode::DependencyGroup group,
6051  Foreign* info);
6052 
6053  void DeoptimizeDependentCodeGroup(Isolate* isolate,
6054  DependentCode::DependencyGroup group);
6055 
6056  bool MarkCodeForDeoptimization(Isolate* isolate,
6057  DependentCode::DependencyGroup group);
6058 
6059  // The following low-level accessors should only be used by this class
6060  // and the mark compact collector.
6061  inline DependentCode* next_link();
6062  inline void set_next_link(DependentCode* next);
6063  inline int count();
6064  inline void set_count(int value);
6065  inline DependencyGroup group();
6066  inline void set_group(DependencyGroup group);
6067  inline Object* object_at(int i);
6068  inline void set_object_at(int i, Object* object);
6069  inline void clear_at(int i);
6070  inline void copy(int from, int to);
6071  DECLARE_CAST(DependentCode)
6072 
6073  static const char* DependencyGroupName(DependencyGroup group);
6074  static void SetMarkedForDeoptimization(Code* code, DependencyGroup group);
6075 
6076  private:
6077  static Handle<DependentCode> Insert(Handle<DependentCode> entries,
6078  DependencyGroup group,
6079  Handle<Object> object);
6080  static Handle<DependentCode> New(DependencyGroup group, Handle<Object> object,
6081  Handle<DependentCode> next);
6082  static Handle<DependentCode> EnsureSpace(Handle<DependentCode> entries);
6083  // Compact by removing cleared weak cells and return true if there was
6084  // any cleared weak cell.
6085  bool Compact();
6086  static int Grow(int number_of_entries) {
6087  if (number_of_entries < 5) return number_of_entries + 1;
6088  return number_of_entries * 5 / 4;
6089  }
6090  inline int flags();
6091  inline void set_flags(int flags);
6092  class GroupField : public BitField<int, 0, 3> {};
6093  class CountField : public BitField<int, 3, 27> {};
6094  STATIC_ASSERT(kGroupCount <= GroupField::kMax + 1);
6095 };

6101 // All heap objects have a Map that describes their structure.
6102 // A Map contains information about:
6103 // - Size information about the object
6104 // - How to iterate over an object (for garbage collection)
6105 class Map: public HeapObject {
6106  public:

6118  // function index in case of primitive maps.
6119  inline int inobject_properties_or_constructor_function_index();

6125  // or the special sentinel value to indicate that there is no object wrapper
6126  // for the primitive (i.e. in case of null or undefined).
6127  static const int kNoConstructorFunctionIndex = 0;
6128  inline int GetConstructorFunctionIndex();

6131  Handle<Map> map, Handle<Context> native_context);
6132

6136

6138  inline InstanceType instance_type();

6140

6142  // instance (only used for JSObject in fast mode).

6145 
6146  // Bit field.
6147  inline byte bit_field() const;
6148  inline void set_bit_field(byte value);

6151  inline byte bit_field2() const;
6152  inline void set_bit_field2(byte value);

6155  inline uint32_t bit_field3() const;

6157 
6158  class EnumLengthBits: public BitField<int,
6159  0, kDescriptorIndexBitCount> {}; // NOLINT
6160  class NumberOfOwnDescriptorsBits: public BitField<int,
6161  kDescriptorIndexBitCount, kDescriptorIndexBitCount> {}; // NOLINT
6162  STATIC_ASSERT(kDescriptorIndexBitCount + kDescriptorIndexBitCount == 20);
6163  class DictionaryMap : public BitField<bool, 20, 1> {};
6164  class OwnsDescriptors : public BitField<bool, 21, 1> {};
6165  class HasHiddenPrototype : public BitField<bool, 22, 1> {};
6166  class Deprecated : public BitField<bool, 23, 1> {};
6167  class IsUnstable : public BitField<bool, 24, 1> {};
6168  class IsMigrationTarget : public BitField<bool, 25, 1> {};
6169  class ImmutablePrototype : public BitField<bool, 26, 1> {};
6170  class NewTargetIsBase : public BitField<bool, 27, 1> {};
6171  // Bit 28 is free.
6172 
6173  // Keep this bit field at the very end for better code in
6174  // Builtins::kJSConstructStubGeneric stub.
6175  // This counter is used for in-object slack tracking.
6176  // The in-object slack tracking is considered enabled when the counter is
6177  // non zero. The counter only has a valid count for initial maps. For
6178  // transitioned maps only kNoSlackTracking has a meaning, namely that inobject
6179  // slack tracking already finished for the transition tree. Any other value
6180  // indicates that either inobject slack tracking is still in progress, or that
6181  // the map isn't part of the transition tree anymore.
6182  class ConstructionCounter : public BitField<int, 29, 3> {};
6183  static const int kSlackTrackingCounterStart = 7;
6184  static const int kSlackTrackingCounterEnd = 1;
6185  static const int kNoSlackTracking = 0;
6186  STATIC_ASSERT(kSlackTrackingCounterStart <= ConstructionCounter::kMax);
6187 
6188 
6189  // Inobject slack tracking is the way to reclaim unused inobject space.
6190  //
6191  // The instance size is initially determined by adding some slack to
6192  // expected_nof_properties (to allow for a few extra properties added
6193  // after the constructor). There is no guarantee that the extra space
6194  // will not be wasted.
6195  //
6196  // Here is the algorithm to reclaim the unused inobject space:
6197  // - Detect the first constructor call for this JSFunction.
6198  // When it happens enter the "in progress" state: initialize construction
6199  // counter in the initial_map.
6200  // - While the tracking is in progress initialize unused properties of a new
6201  // object with one_pointer_filler_map instead of undefined_value (the "used"
6202  // part is initialized with undefined_value as usual). This way they can
6203  // be resized quickly and safely.
6204  // - Once enough objects have been created compute the 'slack'
6205  // (traverse the map transition tree starting from the
6206  // initial_map and find the lowest value of unused_property_fields).
6207  // - Traverse the transition tree again and decrease the instance size
6208  // of every map. Existing objects will resize automatically (they are
6209  // filled with one_pointer_filler_map). All further allocations will
6210  // use the adjusted instance size.
6211  // - SharedFunctionInfo's expected_nof_properties left unmodified since
6212  // allocations made using different closures could actually create different
6213  // kind of objects (see prototype inheritance pattern).
6214  //
6215  // Important: inobject slack tracking is not attempted during the snapshot
6216  // creation.
6217 
6218  static const int kGenerousAllocationCount =
6219  kSlackTrackingCounterStart - kSlackTrackingCounterEnd + 1;
6220 
6221  // Starts the tracking by initializing object constructions countdown counter.
6222  void StartInobjectSlackTracking();
6223 
6224  // True if the object constructions countdown counter is a range
6225  // [kSlackTrackingCounterEnd, kSlackTrackingCounterStart].
6226  inline bool IsInobjectSlackTrackingInProgress();
6227 
6228  // Does the tracking step.
6229  inline void InobjectSlackTrackingStep();
6230 
6231  // Completes inobject slack tracking for the transition tree starting at this
6232  // initial map.
6233  void CompleteInobjectSlackTracking();
6234

6960  // going through this object, or Smi(0) if uninitialized.

6962  // and those of all "downstream" prototypes are invalidated; handlers for a

7247 // List of builtin functions we want to identify to improve code
7248 // generation.
7249 //

7251 // optionally followed by ".prototype", a name of a builtin function

7812  static const int kFormalParameterCountOffset = kLengthOffset + kPointerSize;
7813  static const int kExpectedNofPropertiesOffset =
7814  kFormalParameterCountOffset + kPointerSize;
7815  static const int kNumLiteralsOffset =
7816  kExpectedNofPropertiesOffset + kPointerSize;
7817  static const int kStartPositionAndTypeOffset =
7818  kNumLiteralsOffset + kPointerSize;

7820  kStartPositionAndTypeOffset + kPointerSize;

7822  kEndPositionOffset + kPointerSize;

7824  kFunctionTokenPositionOffset + kPointerSize;

7828  kOptCountAndBailoutReasonOffset + kPointerSize;

7830  kCountersOffset + kPointerSize;
