7832  kAstNodeCountOffset + kPointerSize;
7833 
7834  // Total size.
7835  static const int kSize = kProfilerTicksOffset + kPointerSize;
7836 #else
7837 // The only reason to use smi fields instead of int fields is to allow
7838 // iteration without maps decoding during garbage collections.
7839 // To avoid wasting space on 64-bit architectures we use the following trick:
7840 // we group integer fields into pairs
7841 // The least significant integer in each pair is shifted left by 1. By doing
7842 // this we guarantee that LSB of each kPointerSize aligned word is not set and
7843 // thus this word cannot be treated as pointer to HeapObject during old space
7844 // traversal.
7845 #if V8_TARGET_LITTLE_ENDIAN
7846  static const int kLengthOffset = kLastPointerFieldOffset + kPointerSize;
7847  static const int kFormalParameterCountOffset =
7848  kLengthOffset + kIntSize;
7849 
7850  static const int kExpectedNofPropertiesOffset =
7851  kFormalParameterCountOffset + kIntSize;
7852  static const int kNumLiteralsOffset =
7853  kExpectedNofPropertiesOffset + kIntSize;
7854 
7855  static const int kEndPositionOffset =
7856  kNumLiteralsOffset + kIntSize;
7857  static const int kStartPositionAndTypeOffset =
7858  kEndPositionOffset + kIntSize;
7859 
7860  static const int kFunctionTokenPositionOffset =
7861  kStartPositionAndTypeOffset + kIntSize;
7862  static const int kCompilerHintsOffset =
7863  kFunctionTokenPositionOffset + kIntSize;
7864 
7865  static const int kOptCountAndBailoutReasonOffset =
7866  kCompilerHintsOffset + kIntSize;
7867  static const int kCountersOffset =
7868  kOptCountAndBailoutReasonOffset + kIntSize;
7869 
7870  static const int kAstNodeCountOffset =
7871  kCountersOffset + kIntSize;
7872  static const int kProfilerTicksOffset =
7873  kAstNodeCountOffset + kIntSize;
7874 
7875  // Total size.
7876  static const int kSize = kProfilerTicksOffset + kIntSize;
7877 
7878 #elif V8_TARGET_BIG_ENDIAN
7879  static const int kFormalParameterCountOffset =
7880  kLastPointerFieldOffset + kPointerSize;
7881  static const int kLengthOffset = kFormalParameterCountOffset + kIntSize;
7882 
7883  static const int kNumLiteralsOffset = kLengthOffset + kIntSize;
7884  static const int kExpectedNofPropertiesOffset = kNumLiteralsOffset + kIntSize;
7885 
7886  static const int kStartPositionAndTypeOffset =
7887  kExpectedNofPropertiesOffset + kIntSize;
7888  static const int kEndPositionOffset = kStartPositionAndTypeOffset + kIntSize;
7889 
7890  static const int kCompilerHintsOffset = kEndPositionOffset + kIntSize;
7891  static const int kFunctionTokenPositionOffset =
7892  kCompilerHintsOffset + kIntSize;
7893 
7894  static const int kCountersOffset = kFunctionTokenPositionOffset + kIntSize;
7895  static const int kOptCountAndBailoutReasonOffset = kCountersOffset + kIntSize;
7896 
7897  static const int kProfilerTicksOffset =
7898  kOptCountAndBailoutReasonOffset + kIntSize;
7899  static const int kAstNodeCountOffset = kProfilerTicksOffset + kIntSize;
7900 
7901  // Total size.
7902  static const int kSize = kAstNodeCountOffset + kIntSize;
7903 
7904 #else
7905 #error Unknown byte ordering
7906 #endif // Big endian
7907 #endif // 64-bit

7916  kLastPointerFieldOffset + kPointerSize, kSize>
7917  BodyDescriptorWeakCode;

7919  // Bit positions in start_position_and_type.
7920  // The source code start position is in the 30 most significant bits of
7921  // the start_position_and_type field.
7922  static const int kIsNamedExpressionBit = 0;
7923  static const int kIsTopLevelBit = 1;
7924  static const int kStartPositionShift = 2;
7925  static const int kStartPositionMask = ~((1 << kStartPositionShift) - 1);
7926 
7927  // Bit positions in compiler_hints.
7928  enum CompilerHints {
7929  // byte 0
7930  kAllowLazyCompilation,
7931  kMarkedForTierUp,
7932  kOptimizationDisabled,
7933  kNeverCompiled,
7934  kNative,
7935  kStrictModeFunction,
7936  kUsesArguments,
7937  kNeedsHomeObject,
7938  // byte 1
7939  kHasDuplicateParameters,
7940  kForceInline,
7941  kIsAsmFunction,
7942  kIsAnonymousExpression,
7943  kNameShouldPrintAsAnonymous,
7944  kIsFunction,
7945  kDontCrankshaft,
7946  kDontFlush,
7947  // byte 2
7948  kFunctionKind,
7949  // rest of byte 2 and first two bits of byte 3 are used by FunctionKind
7950  // byte 3
7951  kDeserialized = kFunctionKind + 10,
7952  kIsDeclaration,
7953  kIsAsmWasmBroken,
7954  kRequiresClassFieldInit,
7955  kIsClassFieldInitializer,
7956  kCompilerHintsCount, // Pseudo entry
7957  };
7958  // kFunctionKind has to be byte-aligned
7959  STATIC_ASSERT((kFunctionKind % kBitsPerByte) == 0);
7960 
7961  class FunctionKindBits : public BitField<FunctionKind, kFunctionKind, 10> {};
7962 
7963  class DeoptCountBits : public BitField<int, 0, 4> {};
7964  class OptReenableTriesBits : public BitField<int, 4, 18> {};
7965  class ICAgeBits : public BitField<int, 22, 8> {};
7966 
7967  class OptCountBits : public BitField<int, 0, 22> {};
7968  class DisabledOptimizationReasonBits : public BitField<int, 22, 8> {};
7969 
7970  private:
7971 #if V8_HOST_ARCH_32_BIT
7972  // On 32 bit platforms, compiler hints is a smi.
7973  static const int kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize = kSmiTagSize;
7974  static const int kCompilerHintsSize = kPointerSize;
7975 #else
7976  // On 64 bit platforms, compiler hints is not a smi, see comment above.
7977  static const int kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize = 0;
7978  static const int kCompilerHintsSize = kIntSize;
7979 #endif
7980 
7981  STATIC_ASSERT(SharedFunctionInfo::kCompilerHintsCount +
7982  SharedFunctionInfo::kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize <=
7983  SharedFunctionInfo::kCompilerHintsSize * kBitsPerByte);
7984 
7985  public:
7986  // Constants for optimizing codegen for strict mode function and
7987  // native tests when using integer-width instructions.
7988  static const int kStrictModeBit =
7989  kStrictModeFunction + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize;
7990  static const int kNativeBit = kNative + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize;
7991  static const int kHasDuplicateParametersBit =
7992  kHasDuplicateParameters + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize;
7993 
7994  static const int kFunctionKindShift =
7995  kFunctionKind + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize;
7996  static const int kAllFunctionKindBitsMask = FunctionKindBits::kMask
7997  << kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize;
7998 
7999  static const int kMarkedForTierUpBit =
8000  kMarkedForTierUp + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize;
8001 
8002  // Constants for optimizing codegen for strict mode function and
8003  // native tests.
8004  // Allows to use byte-width instructions.
8005  static const int kStrictModeBitWithinByte = kStrictModeBit % kBitsPerByte;
8006  static const int kNativeBitWithinByte = kNativeBit % kBitsPerByte;
8007  static const int kHasDuplicateParametersBitWithinByte =
8008  kHasDuplicateParametersBit % kBitsPerByte;
8009 
8010  static const int kClassConstructorBitsWithinByte =
8011  FunctionKind::kClassConstructor << kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize;
8012  STATIC_ASSERT(kClassConstructorBitsWithinByte < (1 << kBitsPerByte));
8013 
8014  static const int kMarkedForTierUpBitWithinByte =
8015  kMarkedForTierUpBit % kBitsPerByte;
8016 
8017 #if defined(V8_TARGET_LITTLE_ENDIAN)
8018 #define BYTE_OFFSET(compiler_hint) \
8019  kCompilerHintsOffset + \
8020  (compiler_hint + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) / kBitsPerByte
8021 #elif defined(V8_TARGET_BIG_ENDIAN)
8022 #define BYTE_OFFSET(compiler_hint) \
8023  kCompilerHintsOffset + (kCompilerHintsSize - 1) - \
8024  ((compiler_hint + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) / kBitsPerByte)
8025 #else
8026 #error Unknown byte ordering
8027 #endif
8028  static const int kStrictModeByteOffset = BYTE_OFFSET(kStrictModeFunction);
8029  static const int kNativeByteOffset = BYTE_OFFSET(kNative);
8030  static const int kFunctionKindByteOffset = BYTE_OFFSET(kFunctionKind);
8031  static const int kHasDuplicateParametersByteOffset =
8032  BYTE_OFFSET(kHasDuplicateParameters);
8033  static const int kMarkedForTierUpByteOffset = BYTE_OFFSET(kMarkedForTierUp);
8034 #undef BYTE_OFFSET
8035 
8036  private:
8037  // Returns entry from optimized code map for specified context and OSR entry.
8038  // The result is either kNotFound, or a start index of the context-dependent
8039  // entry.
8040  int SearchOptimizedCodeMapEntry(Context* native_context,
8041  BailoutId osr_ast_id);
8042 
8043  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(SharedFunctionInfo);
8044 };

8147 // A Module object is a mapping from export names to cells

8157  // depending on whether the module has been instantiated and evaluated. See

8184  // otherwise.

8188

8201  static Handle<JSModuleNamespace> GetModuleNamespace(Handle<Module> module,

8222 
8223  // The [must_resolve] argument indicates whether or not an exception should be
8224  // thrown in case the module does not provide an export named [name]
8225  // (including when a cycle is detected). An exception is always thrown in the
8226  // case of conflicting star exports.
8227  //
8228  // If [must_resolve] is true, a null result indicates an exception. If
8229  // [must_resolve] is false, a null result may or may not indicate an
8230  // exception (so check manually!).
8231  class ResolveSet;

8233  Handle<Module> module, Handle<String> name, MessageLocation loc,

8237  MessageLocation loc, bool must_resolve, ResolveSet* resolve_set);
8238

8241  Handle<Module> module, Handle<String> name, MessageLocation loc,
8242  bool must_resolve, ResolveSet* resolve_set);

8244  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(Module);
8245 };

8742 
8743 // Regular expressions
8744 // The regular expression holds a single reference to a FixedArray in
8745 // the kDataOffset field.
8746 // The FixedArray contains the following data:
8747 // - tag : type of regexp implementation (not compiled yet, atom or irregexp)
8748 // - reference to the original source string
8749 // - reference to the original flag string
8750 // If it is an atom regexp
8751 // - a reference to a literal string to search for
8752 // If it is an irregexp regexp:
8753 // - a reference to code for Latin1 inputs (bytecode or compiled), or a smi
8754 // used for tracking the last usage (used for code flushing).
8755 // - a reference to code for UC16 inputs (bytecode or compiled), or a smi
8756 // used for tracking the last usage (used for code flushing)..
8757 // - max number of registers used by irregexp implementations.
8758 // - number of capture registers (output values) of the regexp.
8759 class JSRegExp: public JSObject {
8760  public:
8761  // Meaning of Type:
8762  // NOT_COMPILED: Initial value. No data has been stored in the JSRegExp yet.
8763  // ATOM: A simple string to match against using an indexOf operation.
8764  // IRREGEXP: Compiled with Irregexp.
8765  enum Type { NOT_COMPILED, ATOM, IRREGEXP };
8766  enum Flag {
8767  kNone = 0,
8768  kGlobal = 1 << 0,
8769  kIgnoreCase = 1 << 1,
8770  kMultiline = 1 << 2,
8771  kSticky = 1 << 3,
8772  kUnicode = 1 << 4,
8773  };
8774  typedef base::Flags<Flag> Flags;
8775 
8776  DECL_ACCESSORS(data, Object)
8777  DECL_ACCESSORS(flags, Object)
8778  DECL_ACCESSORS(source, Object)
8779 
8780  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE static MaybeHandle<JSRegExp> New(Handle<String> source,
8781  Flags flags);
8782  static Handle<JSRegExp> Copy(Handle<JSRegExp> regexp);
8783 
8784  static MaybeHandle<JSRegExp> Initialize(Handle<JSRegExp> regexp,
8785  Handle<String> source, Flags flags);
8786  static MaybeHandle<JSRegExp> Initialize(Handle<JSRegExp> regexp,
8787  Handle<String> source,
8788  Handle<String> flags_string);
8789 
8790  inline Type TypeTag();
8791  inline int CaptureCount();
8792  inline Flags GetFlags();
8793  inline String* Pattern();
8794  inline Object* DataAt(int index);
8795  // Set implementation data after the object has been prepared.
8796  inline void SetDataAt(int index, Object* value);
8797 
8798  inline void SetLastIndex(int index);
8799  inline Object* LastIndex();
8800 
8801  static int code_index(bool is_latin1) {
8802  if (is_latin1) {
8803  return kIrregexpLatin1CodeIndex;
8804  } else {
8805  return kIrregexpUC16CodeIndex;
8806  }
8807  }
8808 
8809  static int saved_code_index(bool is_latin1) {
8810  if (is_latin1) {
8811  return kIrregexpLatin1CodeSavedIndex;
8812  } else {
8813  return kIrregexpUC16CodeSavedIndex;
8814  }
8815  }
8816 
8817  DECLARE_CAST(JSRegExp)
8818 
8819  // Dispatched behavior.
8820  DECLARE_PRINTER(JSRegExp)
8821  DECLARE_VERIFIER(JSRegExp)
8822 
8823  static const int kDataOffset = JSObject::kHeaderSize;
8824  static const int kSourceOffset = kDataOffset + kPointerSize;
8825  static const int kFlagsOffset = kSourceOffset + kPointerSize;
8826  static const int kSize = kFlagsOffset + kPointerSize;
8827 
8828  // Indices in the data array.
8829  static const int kTagIndex = 0;
8830  static const int kSourceIndex = kTagIndex + 1;
8831  static const int kFlagsIndex = kSourceIndex + 1;
8832  static const int kDataIndex = kFlagsIndex + 1;
8833  // The data fields are used in different ways depending on the
8834  // value of the tag.
8835  // Atom regexps (literal strings).
8836  static const int kAtomPatternIndex = kDataIndex;
8837 
8838  static const int kAtomDataSize = kAtomPatternIndex + 1;
8839 
8840  // Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for Latin1. If compilation
8841  // fails, this fields hold an exception object that should be
8842  // thrown if the regexp is used again.
8843  static const int kIrregexpLatin1CodeIndex = kDataIndex;
8844  // Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for UC16. If compilation
8845  // fails, this fields hold an exception object that should be
8846  // thrown if the regexp is used again.
8847  static const int kIrregexpUC16CodeIndex = kDataIndex + 1;
8848 
8849  // Saved instance of Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for Latin1 that
8850  // is a potential candidate for flushing.
8851  static const int kIrregexpLatin1CodeSavedIndex = kDataIndex + 2;
8852  // Saved instance of Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for UC16 that is
8853  // a potential candidate for flushing.
8854  static const int kIrregexpUC16CodeSavedIndex = kDataIndex + 3;
8855 
8856  // Maximal number of registers used by either Latin1 or UC16.
8857  // Only used to check that there is enough stack space
8858  static const int kIrregexpMaxRegisterCountIndex = kDataIndex + 4;
8859  // Number of captures in the compiled regexp.
8860  static const int kIrregexpCaptureCountIndex = kDataIndex + 5;
8861  // Maps names of named capture groups (at indices 2i) to their corresponding
8862  // capture group indices (at indices 2i + 1).
8863  static const int kIrregexpCaptureNameMapIndex = kDataIndex + 6;
8864 
8865  static const int kIrregexpDataSize = kIrregexpCaptureNameMapIndex + 1;
8866 
8867  // Offsets directly into the data fixed array.
8868  static const int kDataTagOffset =
8869  FixedArray::kHeaderSize + kTagIndex * kPointerSize;
8870  static const int kDataOneByteCodeOffset =

8917 
8918 // This cache is used in two different variants. For regexp caching, it simply
8919 // maps identifying info of the regexp to the cached regexp object. Scripts and
8920 // eval code only gets cached after a second probe for the code object. To do
8921 // so, on first "put" only a hash identifying the source is entered into the
8922 // cache, mapping it to a lifetime count of the hash. On each call to Age all
8923 // such lifetimes get reduced, and removed once they reach zero. If a second put
8924 // is called while such a hash is live in the cache, the hash gets replaced by
8925 // an actual cache entry. Age also removes stale live entries from the cache.
8926 // Such entries are identified by SharedFunctionInfos pointing to either the
8927 // recompilation stub, or to "old" code. This avoids memory leaks due to
8928 // premature caching of scripts and eval strings that are never needed later.
8929 class CompilationCacheTable: public HashTable<CompilationCacheTable,
8930  CompilationCacheShape,
8931  HashTableKey*> {
8932  public:
8933  // Find cached value for a string key, otherwise return null.
8934  Handle<Object> Lookup(
8935  Handle<String> src, Handle<Context> context, LanguageMode language_mode);
8936  Handle<Object> LookupEval(
8937  Handle<String> src, Handle<SharedFunctionInfo> shared,
8938  LanguageMode language_mode, int scope_position);
8939  Handle<Object> LookupRegExp(Handle<String> source, JSRegExp::Flags flags);
8940  static Handle<CompilationCacheTable> Put(
8941  Handle<CompilationCacheTable> cache, Handle<String> src,
8942  Handle<Context> context, LanguageMode language_mode,
8943  Handle<Object> value);
8944  static Handle<CompilationCacheTable> PutEval(
8945  Handle<CompilationCacheTable> cache, Handle<String> src,
8946  Handle<SharedFunctionInfo> context, Handle<SharedFunctionInfo> value,
8947  int scope_position);
8948  static Handle<CompilationCacheTable> PutRegExp(
8949  Handle<CompilationCacheTable> cache, Handle<String> src,
8950  JSRegExp::Flags flags, Handle<FixedArray> value);
8951  void Remove(Object* value);
8952  void Age();
8953  static const int kHashGenerations = 10;
8954 
8955  DECLARE_CAST(CompilationCacheTable)
8956 
8957  private:
8958  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(CompilationCacheTable);
8959 };

9317 // The characteristics of a string are stored in its map. Retrieving these
9318 // few bits of information is moderately expensive, involving two memory
9319 // loads where the second is dependent on the first. To improve efficiency
9320 // the shape of the string is given its own class so that it can be retrieved
9321 // once and used for several string operations. A StringShape is small enough
9322 // to be passed by value and is immutable, but be aware that flattening a
9323 // string can potentially alter its shape. Also be aware that a GC caused by
9324 // something else can alter the shape of a string due to ConsString
9325 // shortcutting. Keeping these restrictions in mind has proven to be error-
9326 // prone and so we no longer put StringShapes in variables unless there is a
9327 // concrete performance benefit at that particular point in the code.
9328 class StringShape BASE_EMBEDDED {
9329  public:
9330  inline explicit StringShape(const String* s);
9331  inline explicit StringShape(Map* s);
9332  inline explicit StringShape(InstanceType t);
9333  inline bool IsSequential();
9334  inline bool IsExternal();
9335  inline bool IsCons();
9336  inline bool IsSliced();
9337  inline bool IsIndirect();
9338  inline bool IsExternalOneByte();
9339  inline bool IsExternalTwoByte();
9340  inline bool IsSequentialOneByte();
9341  inline bool IsSequentialTwoByte();
9342  inline bool IsInternalized();
9343  inline StringRepresentationTag representation_tag();
9344  inline uint32_t encoding_tag();
9345  inline uint32_t full_representation_tag();
9346  inline uint32_t size_tag();
9347 #ifdef DEBUG
9348  inline uint32_t type() { return type_; }
9349  inline void invalidate() { valid_ = false; }
9350  inline bool valid() { return valid_; }
9351 #else
9352  inline void invalidate() { }
9353 #endif
9354 
9355  private:
9356  uint32_t type_;
9357 #ifdef DEBUG
9358  inline void set_valid() { valid_ = true; }
9359  bool valid_;
9360 #else
9361  inline void set_valid() { }
9362 #endif
9363 };

9366 // The Name abstract class captures anything that can be used as a property
9367 // name, i.e., strings and symbols. All names store a hash value.
9368 class Name: public HeapObject {
9369  public:
9370  // Get and set the hash field of the name.
9371  inline uint32_t hash_field();
9372  inline void set_hash_field(uint32_t value);
9373 
9374  // Tells whether the hash code has been computed.
9375  inline bool HasHashCode();
9376 
9377  // Returns a hash value used for the property table
9378  inline uint32_t Hash();
9379 
9380  // Equality operations.
9381  inline bool Equals(Name* other);
9382  inline static bool Equals(Handle<Name> one, Handle<Name> two);
9383 
9384  // Conversion.
9385  inline bool AsArrayIndex(uint32_t* index);
9386 
9387  // If the name is private, it can only name own properties.
9388  inline bool IsPrivate();
9389 
9390  inline bool IsUniqueName() const;
9391 
9392  // Return a string version of this name that is converted according to the
9393  // rules described in ES6 section 9.2.11.
9394  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<String> ToFunctionName(Handle<Name> name);
9395  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<String> ToFunctionName(
9396  Handle<Name> name, Handle<String> prefix);
9397 
9398  DECLARE_CAST(Name)
9399 
9400  DECLARE_PRINTER(Name)
9401 #if TRACE_MAPS
9402  void NameShortPrint();
9403  int NameShortPrint(Vector<char> str);
9404 #endif
9405 
9406  // Layout description.
9407  static const int kHashFieldSlot = HeapObject::kHeaderSize;
9408 #if V8_TARGET_LITTLE_ENDIAN || !V8_HOST_ARCH_64_BIT
9409  static const int kHashFieldOffset = kHashFieldSlot;
9410 #else
9411  static const int kHashFieldOffset = kHashFieldSlot + kIntSize;
9412 #endif
9413  static const int kSize = kHashFieldSlot + kPointerSize;
9414 
9415  // Mask constant for checking if a name has a computed hash code
9416  // and if it is a string that is an array index. The least significant bit
9417  // indicates whether a hash code has been computed. If the hash code has
9418  // been computed the 2nd bit tells whether the string can be used as an
9419  // array index.
9420  static const int kHashNotComputedMask = 1;
9421  static const int kIsNotArrayIndexMask = 1 << 1;
9422  static const int kNofHashBitFields = 2;
9423 
9424  // Shift constant retrieving hash code from hash field.
9425  static const int kHashShift = kNofHashBitFields;
9426 
9427  // Only these bits are relevant in the hash, since the top two are shifted
9428  // out.
9429  static const uint32_t kHashBitMask = 0xffffffffu >> kHashShift;
9430 
9431  // Array index strings this short can keep their index in the hash field.
9432  static const int kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength = 7;
9433 
9434  // Maximum number of characters to consider when trying to convert a string
9435  // value into an array index.
9436  static const int kMaxArrayIndexSize = 10;
9437 
9438  // For strings which are array indexes the hash value has the string length
9439  // mixed into the hash, mainly to avoid a hash value of zero which would be
9440  // the case for the string '0'. 24 bits are used for the array index value.
9441  static const int kArrayIndexValueBits = 24;
9442  static const int kArrayIndexLengthBits =
9443  kBitsPerInt - kArrayIndexValueBits - kNofHashBitFields;
9444 
9445  STATIC_ASSERT(kArrayIndexLengthBits > 0);
9446  STATIC_ASSERT(kMaxArrayIndexSize < (1 << kArrayIndexLengthBits));
9447 
9448  class ArrayIndexValueBits : public BitField<unsigned int, kNofHashBitFields,
9449  kArrayIndexValueBits> {}; // NOLINT
9450  class ArrayIndexLengthBits : public BitField<unsigned int,
9451  kNofHashBitFields + kArrayIndexValueBits,
9452  kArrayIndexLengthBits> {}; // NOLINT
9453 
9454  // Check that kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength + 1 is a power of two so we
9455  // could use a mask to test if the length of string is less than or equal to
9456  // kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength.
9457  STATIC_ASSERT(IS_POWER_OF_TWO(kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength + 1));
9458 
9459  static const unsigned int kContainsCachedArrayIndexMask =
9460  (~static_cast<unsigned>(kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength)
9461  << ArrayIndexLengthBits::kShift) |
9462  kIsNotArrayIndexMask;
9463 
9464  // Value of empty hash field indicating that the hash is not computed.
9465  static const int kEmptyHashField =
9466  kIsNotArrayIndexMask | kHashNotComputedMask;
9467 
9468  protected:
9469  static inline bool IsHashFieldComputed(uint32_t field);
9470 
9471  private:

9524 // The String abstract class captures JavaScript string values:
9525 //
9526 // Ecma-262:
9527 // 4.3.16 String Value
9528 // A string value is a member of the type String and is a finite
9529 // ordered sequence of zero or more 16-bit unsigned integer values.
9530 //
9531 // All string values have a length field.
9532 class String: public Name {
9533  public:
9534  enum Encoding { ONE_BYTE_ENCODING, TWO_BYTE_ENCODING };
9535 
9536  class SubStringRange {
9537  public:
9538  explicit inline SubStringRange(String* string, int first = 0,
9539  int length = -1);
9540  class iterator;
9541  inline iterator begin();
9542  inline iterator end();
9543 
9544  private:
9545  String* string_;
9546  int first_;
9547  int length_;
9548  };
9549 
9550  // Representation of the flat content of a String.
9551  // A non-flat string doesn't have flat content.
9552  // A flat string has content that's encoded as a sequence of either
9553  // one-byte chars or two-byte UC16.
9554  // Returned by String::GetFlatContent().
9555  class FlatContent {
9556  public:
9557  // Returns true if the string is flat and this structure contains content.
9558  bool IsFlat() const { return state_ != NON_FLAT; }
9559  // Returns true if the structure contains one-byte content.
9560  bool IsOneByte() const { return state_ == ONE_BYTE; }
9561  // Returns true if the structure contains two-byte content.
9562  bool IsTwoByte() const { return state_ == TWO_BYTE; }
9563 
9564  // Return the one byte content of the string. Only use if IsOneByte()
9565  // returns true.
9566  Vector<const uint8_t> ToOneByteVector() const {
9567  DCHECK_EQ(ONE_BYTE, state_);
9568  return Vector<const uint8_t>(onebyte_start, length_);
9569  }
9570  // Return the two-byte content of the string. Only use if IsTwoByte()
9571  // returns true.
9572  Vector<const uc16> ToUC16Vector() const {
9573  DCHECK_EQ(TWO_BYTE, state_);
9574  return Vector<const uc16>(twobyte_start, length_);
9575  }
9576 
9577  uc16 Get(int i) const {
9578  DCHECK(i < length_);
9579  DCHECK(state_ != NON_FLAT);
9580  if (state_ == ONE_BYTE) return onebyte_start[i];
9581  return twobyte_start[i];
9582  }
9583 
9584  bool UsesSameString(const FlatContent& other) const {
9585  return onebyte_start == other.onebyte_start;
9586  }
9587 
9588  private:
9589  enum State { NON_FLAT, ONE_BYTE, TWO_BYTE };
9590 
9591  // Constructors only used by String::GetFlatContent().
9592  explicit FlatContent(const uint8_t* start, int length)
9593  : onebyte_start(start), length_(length), state_(ONE_BYTE) {}
9594  explicit FlatContent(const uc16* start, int length)
9595  : twobyte_start(start), length_(length), state_(TWO_BYTE) { }
9596  FlatContent() : onebyte_start(NULL), length_(0), state_(NON_FLAT) { }
9597 
9598  union {
9599  const uint8_t* onebyte_start;
9600  const uc16* twobyte_start;
9601  };
9602  int length_;
9603  State state_;
9604 
9605  friend class String;
9606  friend class IterableSubString;
9607  };

9647  // Flattens the string. Checks first inline to see if it is
9648  // necessary. Does nothing if the string is not a cons string.
9649  // Flattening allocates a sequential string with the same data as
9650  // the given string and mutates the cons string to a degenerate
9651  // form, where the first component is the new sequential string and
9652  // the second component is the empty string. If allocation fails,
9653  // this function returns a failure. If flattening succeeds, this
9654  // function returns the sequential string that is now the first
9655  // component of the cons string.
9656  //
9657  // Degenerate cons strings are handled specially by the garbage
9658  // collector (see IsShortcutCandidate).

9674  // String relational comparison, implemented according to ES6 section 7.2.11
9675  // Abstract Relational Comparison (step 5): The comparison of Strings uses a
9676  // simple lexicographic ordering on sequences of code unit values. There is no
9677  // attempt to use the more complex, semantically oriented definitions of
9678  // character or string equality and collating order defined in the Unicode
9679  // specification. Therefore String values that are canonically equal according
9680  // to the Unicode standard could test as unequal. In effect this algorithm
9681  // assumes that both Strings are already in normalized form. Also, note that
9682  // for strings containing supplementary characters, lexicographic ordering on
9683  // sequences of UTF-16 code unit values differs from that on sequences of code
9684  // point values.
9685  MUST_USE_RESULT static ComparisonResult Compare(Handle<String> x,
9686  Handle<String> y);

9797  // Helper function for flattening strings.

9803 
9804  // The return value may point to the first aligned word containing the first
9805  // non-one-byte character, rather than directly to the non-one-byte character.
9806  // If the return value is >= the passed length, the entire string was
9807  // one-byte.
9808  static inline int NonAsciiStart(const char* chars, int length) {
9809  const char* start = chars;
9810  const char* limit = chars + length;
9811 
9812  if (length >= kIntptrSize) {
9813  // Check unaligned bytes.
9814  while (!IsAligned(reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(chars), sizeof(uintptr_t))) {
9815  if (static_cast<uint8_t>(*chars) > unibrow::Utf8::kMaxOneByteChar) {
9816  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9817  }
9818  ++chars;
9819  }
9820  // Check aligned words.
9821  DCHECK(unibrow::Utf8::kMaxOneByteChar == 0x7F);
9822  const uintptr_t non_one_byte_mask = kUintptrAllBitsSet / 0xFF * 0x80;
9823  while (chars + sizeof(uintptr_t) <= limit) {
9824  if (*reinterpret_cast<const uintptr_t*>(chars) & non_one_byte_mask) {
9825  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9826  }
9827  chars += sizeof(uintptr_t);
9828  }
9829  }
9830  // Check remaining unaligned bytes.
9831  while (chars < limit) {
9832  if (static_cast<uint8_t>(*chars) > unibrow::Utf8::kMaxOneByteChar) {
9833  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9834  }
9835  ++chars;
9836  }
9837 
9838  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9839  }
9840 
9841  static inline bool IsAscii(const char* chars, int length) {
9842  return NonAsciiStart(chars, length) >= length;
9843  }
9844 
9845  static inline bool IsAscii(const uint8_t* chars, int length) {
9846  return
9847  NonAsciiStart(reinterpret_cast<const char*>(chars), length) >= length;
9848  }
9849 
9850  static inline int NonOneByteStart(const uc16* chars, int length) {
9851  const uc16* limit = chars + length;
9852  const uc16* start = chars;
9853  while (chars < limit) {
9854  if (*chars > kMaxOneByteCharCodeU) return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9855  ++chars;
9856  }
9857  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9858  }
9859 
9860  static inline bool IsOneByte(const uc16* chars, int length) {
9861  return NonOneByteStart(chars, length) >= length;
9862  }
9863

9866  String* string,
9867  int offset = 0);

9870  bool include_ending_line);

9873  // when deserializing an internalized string.
9874  inline void SetForwardedInternalizedString(String* string);
9875  inline String* GetForwardedInternalizedString();
9876 
9877  private:

9879  friend class StringTableInsertionKey;
9880

9882  PretenureFlag tenure);
9883

9885  // but it is most efficient on strings that are almost flat.
9886  bool SlowEquals(String* other);
9887 
9888  static bool SlowEquals(Handle<String> one, Handle<String> two);
9889 
9890  // Slow case of AsArrayIndex.

9994 // The ConsString class describes string values built by using the
9995 // addition operator on strings. A ConsString is a pair where the
9996 // first and second components are pointers to other string values.
9997 // One or both components of a ConsString can be pointers to other
9998 // ConsStrings, creating a binary tree of ConsStrings where the leaves
9999 // are non-ConsString string values. The string value represented by
10000 // a ConsString can be obtained by concatenating the leaf string
10001 // values in a left-to-right depth-first traversal of the tree.

10010  WriteBarrierMode mode = UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER);
10011 
10012  // Second string of the cons cell.
10013  inline String* second();
10014  // Doesn't check that the result is a string, even in debug mode. This is
10015  // useful during GC where the mark bits confuse the checks.
10016  inline Object* unchecked_second();
10017  inline void set_second(String* second,
10018  WriteBarrierMode mode = UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER);
10019 
10020  // Dispatched behavior.
10021  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE uint16_t ConsStringGet(int index);
10022 
10023  DECLARE_CAST(ConsString)
10024

10026  static const int kFirstOffset = POINTER_SIZE_ALIGN(String::kSize);
10027  static const int kSecondOffset = kFirstOffset + kPointerSize;
10028  static const int kSize = kSecondOffset + kPointerSize;
10029 
10030  // Minimum length for a cons string.
10031  static const int kMinLength = 13;

10034  BodyDescriptor;

10042 
10043 // The Sliced String class describes strings that are substrings of another
10044 // sequential string. The motivation is to save time and memory when creating
10045 // a substring. A Sliced String is described as a pointer to the parent,
10046 // the offset from the start of the parent string and the length. Using
10047 // a Sliced String therefore requires unpacking of the parent string and
10048 // adding the offset to the start address. A substring of a Sliced String
10049 // are not nested since the double indirection is simplified when creating
10050 // such a substring.
10051 // Currently missing features are:
10052 // - handling externalized parent strings
10053 // - external strings as parent
10054 // - truncating sliced string to enable otherwise unneeded parent to be GC'ed.
10055 class SlicedString: public String {
10056  public:
10057  inline String* parent();
10058  inline void set_parent(String* parent,
10059  WriteBarrierMode mode = UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER);
10060  inline int offset() const;
10061  inline void set_offset(int offset);
10062 
10063  // Dispatched behavior.
10064  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE uint16_t SlicedStringGet(int index);
10065 
10066  DECLARE_CAST(SlicedString)
10067 
10068  // Layout description.
10069  static const int kParentOffset = POINTER_SIZE_ALIGN(String::kSize);
10070  static const int kOffsetOffset = kParentOffset + kPointerSize;
10071  static const int kSize = kOffsetOffset + kPointerSize;
10072 
10073  // Minimum length for a sliced string.
10074  static const int kMinLength = 13;
10075 
10076  typedef FixedBodyDescriptor<kParentOffset,
10077  kOffsetOffset + kPointerSize, kSize>
10078  BodyDescriptor;
10079 
10080  DECLARE_VERIFIER(SlicedString)
10081 
10082  private:

10087 // The ExternalString class describes string values that are backed by
10088 // a string resource that lies outside the V8 heap. ExternalStrings
10089 // consist of the length field common to all strings, a pointer to the
10090 // external resource. It is important to ensure (externally) that the
10091 // resource is not deallocated while the ExternalString is live in the
10092 // V8 heap.
10093 //
10094 // The API expects that all ExternalStrings are created through the
10095 // API. Therefore, ExternalStrings should not be used internally.
10096 class ExternalString: public String {
10097  public:
10098  DECLARE_CAST(ExternalString)
10099 
10100  // Layout description.
10101  static const int kResourceOffset = POINTER_SIZE_ALIGN(String::kSize);
10102  static const int kShortSize = kResourceOffset + kPointerSize;
10103  static const int kResourceDataOffset = kResourceOffset + kPointerSize;
10104  static const int kSize = kResourceDataOffset + kPointerSize;
10105 
10106  // Return whether external string is short (data pointer is not cached).
10107  inline bool is_short();
10108 
10109  STATIC_ASSERT(kResourceOffset == Internals::kStringResourceOffset);
10110 
10111  private:
10112  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(ExternalString);
10113 };

10226 
10227 // This maintains an off-stack representation of the stack frames required
10228 // to traverse a ConsString, allowing an entirely iterative and restartable
10229 // traversal of the entire string
10230 class ConsStringIterator {
10231  public:
10232  inline ConsStringIterator() {}
10233  inline explicit ConsStringIterator(ConsString* cons_string, int offset = 0) {
10234  Reset(cons_string, offset);
10235  }
10236  inline void Reset(ConsString* cons_string, int offset = 0) {
10237  depth_ = 0;
10238  // Next will always return NULL.
10239  if (cons_string == NULL) return;
10240  Initialize(cons_string, offset);
10241  }
10242  // Returns NULL when complete.
10243  inline String* Next(int* offset_out) {
10244  *offset_out = 0;
10245  if (depth_ == 0) return NULL;
10246  return Continue(offset_out);
10247  }
10248 
10249  private:
10250  static const int kStackSize = 32;
10251  // Use a mask instead of doing modulo operations for stack wrapping.
10252  static const int kDepthMask = kStackSize-1;
10253  STATIC_ASSERT(IS_POWER_OF_TWO(kStackSize));
10254  static inline int OffsetForDepth(int depth);
10255 
10256  inline void PushLeft(ConsString* string);
10257  inline void PushRight(ConsString* string);
10258  inline void AdjustMaximumDepth();
10259  inline void Pop();
10260  inline bool StackBlown() { return maximum_depth_ - depth_ == kStackSize; }
10261  void Initialize(ConsString* cons_string, int offset);
10262  String* Continue(int* offset_out);
10263  String* NextLeaf(bool* blew_stack);
10264  String* Search(int* offset_out);
10265 
10266  // Stack must always contain only frames for which right traversal
10267  // has not yet been performed.
10268  ConsString* frames_[kStackSize];
10269  ConsString* root_;
10270  int depth_;
10271  int maximum_depth_;
10272  int consumed_;
10273  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(ConsStringIterator);
10274 };

10278  public:
10279  inline StringCharacterStream(String* string,
10280  int offset = 0);
10281  inline uint16_t GetNext();
10282  inline bool HasMore();
10283  inline void Reset(String* string, int offset = 0);
10284  inline void VisitOneByteString(const uint8_t* chars, int length);

10303  explicit VectorIterator(Vector<const T> data) : data_(data), index_(0) { }

10727 
10728 // OrderedHashTableIterator is an iterator that iterates over the keys and
10729 // values of an OrderedHashTable.
10730 //
10731 // The iterator has a reference to the underlying OrderedHashTable data,
10732 // [table], as well as the current [index] the iterator is at.
10733 //
10734 // When the OrderedHashTable is rehashed it adds a reference from the old table
10735 // to the new table as well as storing enough data about the changes so that the
10736 // iterator [index] can be adjusted accordingly.
10737 //
10738 // When the [Next] result from the iterator is requested, the iterator checks if
10739 // there is a newer table that it needs to transition to.
10740 template<class Derived, class TableType>
10741 class OrderedHashTableIterator: public JSObject {
10742  public:
10743  // [table]: the backing hash table mapping keys to values.
10744  DECL_ACCESSORS(table, Object)
10745 
10746  // [index]: The index into the data table.
10747  DECL_ACCESSORS(index, Object)
10748 
10749  // [kind]: The kind of iteration this is. One of the [Kind] enum values.
10750  DECL_ACCESSORS(kind, Object)
10751 
10752 #ifdef OBJECT_PRINT
10753  void OrderedHashTableIteratorPrint(std::ostream& os); // NOLINT
10754 #endif
10755 
10756  static const int kTableOffset = JSObject::kHeaderSize;
10757  static const int kIndexOffset = kTableOffset + kPointerSize;
10758  static const int kKindOffset = kIndexOffset + kPointerSize;
10759  static const int kSize = kKindOffset + kPointerSize;
10760 
10761  enum Kind {
10762  kKindKeys = 1,
10763  kKindValues = 2,
10764  kKindEntries = 3
10765  };
10766 
10767  // Whether the iterator has more elements. This needs to be called before
10768  // calling |CurrentKey| and/or |CurrentValue|.
10769  bool HasMore();
10770 
10771  // Move the index forward one.
10772  void MoveNext() {
10773  set_index(Smi::FromInt(Smi::cast(index())->value() + 1));
10774  }
10775 
10776  // Populates the array with the next key and value and then moves the iterator
10777  // forward.
10778  // This returns the |kind| or 0 if the iterator is already at the end.
10779  Smi* Next(JSArray* value_array);
10780 
10781  // Returns the current key of the iterator. This should only be called when
10782  // |HasMore| returns true.
10783  inline Object* CurrentKey();
10784 
10785  private:
10786  // Transitions the iterator to the non obsolete backing store. This is a NOP
10787  // if the [table] is not obsolete.
10788  void Transition();
10789 
10790  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(OrderedHashTableIterator);
10791 };
10792

11085 // The JSArray describes JavaScript Arrays
11086 // Such an array can be in one of two modes:
11087 // - fast, backing storage is a FixedArray and length <= elements.length();
11088 // Please note: push and pop can be used to grow and shrink the array.
11089 // - slow, backing storage is a HashTable with numbers as keys.
11090 class JSArray: public JSObject {
11091  public:
11092  // [length]: The length property.
11093  DECL_ACCESSORS(length, Object)
11094

11096  // is set to a smi. This matches the set function on FixedArray.
11097  inline void set_length(Smi* length);

11100  static bool WouldChangeReadOnlyLength(Handle<JSArray> array, uint32_t index);
11101 
11102  // Initialize the array with the given capacity. The function may
11103  // fail due to out-of-memory situations, but only if the requested
11104  // capacity is non-zero.
11105  static void Initialize(Handle<JSArray> array, int capacity, int length = 0);
11106 
11107  // If the JSArray has fast elements, and new_length would result in
11108  // normalization, returns true.
11109  bool SetLengthWouldNormalize(uint32_t new_length);
11110  static inline bool SetLengthWouldNormalize(Heap* heap, uint32_t new_length);
11111 
11112  // Initializes the array to a certain length.
11113  inline bool AllowsSetLength();
11114 
11115  static void SetLength(Handle<JSArray> array, uint32_t length);
11116 
11117  // Set the content of the array to the content of storage.
11118  static inline void SetContent(Handle<JSArray> array,
11119  Handle<FixedArrayBase> storage);
11120 
11121  // ES6 9.4.2.1
11122  MUST_USE_RESULT static Maybe<bool> DefineOwnProperty(
11123  Isolate* isolate, Handle<JSArray> o, Handle<Object> name,
11124  PropertyDescriptor* desc, ShouldThrow should_throw);
11125

11130  Handle<JSArray> a,
11131  PropertyDescriptor* desc,
11132  ShouldThrow should_throw);
11133 
11134  // Checks whether the Array has the current realm's Array.prototype as its
11135  // prototype. This function is best-effort and only gives a conservative
11136  // approximation, erring on the side of false, in particular with respect
11137  // to Proxies and objects with a hidden prototype.
11138  inline bool HasArrayPrototype(Isolate* isolate);
11139

11154  (kMaxRegularHeapObjectSize - FixedArray::kHeaderSize - kSize -
11155  AllocationMemento::kSize) /
11156  kPointerSize;

11187 // An accessor must have a getter, but can have no setter.
11188 //
11189 // When setting a property, V8 searches accessors in prototypes.
11190 // If an accessor was found and it does not have a setter,
11191 // the request is ignored.
11192 //
11193 // If the accessor in the prototype has the READ_ONLY property attribute, then
11194 // a new value is added to the derived object when the property is set.
11195 // This shadows the accessor in the prototype.
11196 class AccessorInfo: public Struct {
11197  public:

11202  DECL_ACCESSORS(getter, Object)
11203  DECL_ACCESSORS(setter, Object)
11204  // This either points at the same as above, or a trampoline in case we are
11205  // running with the simulator. Use these entries from generated code.
11206  DECL_ACCESSORS(js_getter, Object)
11207  DECL_ACCESSORS(data, Object)
11208 
11209  static Address redirect(Isolate* isolate, Address address,
11210  AccessorComponent component);
11211  Address redirected_getter() const;
11212 
11213  // Dispatched behavior.
11214  DECLARE_PRINTER(AccessorInfo)
11215 
11216  inline bool all_can_read();
11217  inline void set_all_can_read(bool value);
11218 
11219  inline bool all_can_write();
11220  inline void set_all_can_write(bool value);
11221

11229  inline void set_is_sloppy(bool value);
11230

11232  inline void set_property_attributes(PropertyAttributes attributes);
11233 
11234  // Checks whether the given receiver is compatible with this accessor.
11235  static bool IsCompatibleReceiverMap(Isolate* isolate,
11236  Handle<AccessorInfo> info,

11239 
11240  DECLARE_CAST(AccessorInfo)
11241

11243  DECLARE_VERIFIER(AccessorInfo)
11244

11246  // Return number added.

11248  Handle<FixedArray> array,

11267  static const int kSpecialDataProperty = 2;

11276 // Support for JavaScript accessors: A pair of a getter and a setter. Each
11277 // accessor can either be
11278 // * a pointer to a JavaScript function or proxy: a real accessor
11279 // * undefined: considered an accessor by the spec, too, strangely enough
11280 // * the hole: an accessor which has not been set
11281 // * a pointer to a map: a transition used to ensure map sharing
11282 class AccessorPair: public Struct {
11283  public:
11284  DECL_ACCESSORS(getter, Object)
11285  DECL_ACCESSORS(setter, Object)
11286 
11287  DECLARE_CAST(AccessorPair)
11288

11290 
11291  inline Object* get(AccessorComponent component);
11292  inline void set(AccessorComponent component, Object* value);
11293 
11294  // Note: Returns undefined instead in case of a hole.
11295  static Handle<Object> GetComponent(Handle<AccessorPair> accessor_pair,
11296  AccessorComponent component);
11297 
11298  // Set both components, skipping arguments which are a JavaScript null.
11299  inline void SetComponents(Object* getter, Object* setter);
11300 
11301  inline bool Equals(AccessorPair* pair);
11302  inline bool Equals(Object* getter_value, Object* setter_value);
11303 
11304  inline bool ContainsAccessor();
11305 
11306  // Dispatched behavior.
11307  DECLARE_PRINTER(AccessorPair)
11308  DECLARE_VERIFIER(AccessorPair)
11309 
11310  static const int kGetterOffset = HeapObject::kHeaderSize;
11311  static const int kSetterOffset = kGetterOffset + kPointerSize;
11312  static const int kSize = kSetterOffset + kPointerSize;
11313 
11314  private:
11315  // Strangely enough, in addition to functions and harmony proxies, the spec
11316  // requires us to consider undefined as a kind of accessor, too:
11317  // var obj = {};
11318  // Object.defineProperty(obj, "foo", {get: undefined});
11319  // assertTrue("foo" in obj);
11320  inline bool IsJSAccessor(Object* obj);
11321 
11322  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(AccessorPair);
11323 };

11691 // Abstract base class for visiting, and optionally modifying, the
11692 // pointers contained in Objects. Used in GC and serialization/deserialization.
11693 class ObjectVisitor BASE_EMBEDDED {
11694  public:
11695  virtual ~ObjectVisitor() {}
11696 
11697  // Visits a contiguous arrays of pointers in the half-open range
11698  // [start, end). Any or all of the values may be modified on return.
11699  virtual void VisitPointers(Object** start, Object** end) = 0;
11700 
11701  // Handy shorthand for visiting a single pointer.
11702  virtual void VisitPointer(Object** p) { VisitPointers(p, p + 1); }
11703 
11704  // Visit weak next_code_link in Code object.
11705  virtual void VisitNextCodeLink(Object** p) { VisitPointers(p, p + 1); }
11706 
11707  // To allow lazy clearing of inline caches the visitor has
11708  // a rich interface for iterating over Code objects..
11709 
11710  // Visits a code target in the instruction stream.
11711  virtual void VisitCodeTarget(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11712 
11713  // Visits a code entry in a JS function.
11714  virtual void VisitCodeEntry(Address entry_address);
11715 
11716  // Visits a global property cell reference in the instruction stream.
11717  virtual void VisitCell(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11718 
11719  // Visits a runtime entry in the instruction stream.
11720  virtual void VisitRuntimeEntry(RelocInfo* rinfo) {}
11721 
11722  // Visits the resource of an one-byte or two-byte string.
11723  virtual void VisitExternalOneByteString(
11724  v8::String::ExternalOneByteStringResource** resource) {}
11725  virtual void VisitExternalTwoByteString(
11726  v8::String::ExternalStringResource** resource) {}
11727 
11728  // Visits a debug call target in the instruction stream.
11729  virtual void VisitDebugTarget(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11730 
11731  // Visits the byte sequence in a function's prologue that contains information
11732  // about the code's age.
11733  virtual void VisitCodeAgeSequence(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11734 
11735  // Visit pointer embedded into a code object.
11736  virtual void VisitEmbeddedPointer(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11737 
11738  // Visits an external reference embedded into a code object.
11739  virtual void VisitExternalReference(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11740 
11741  // Visits an external reference.
11742  virtual void VisitExternalReference(Address* p) {}
11743 
11744  // Visits an (encoded) internal reference.
11745  virtual void VisitInternalReference(RelocInfo* rinfo) {}
11746 
11747  // Visits a handle that has an embedder-assigned class ID.
11748  virtual void VisitEmbedderReference(Object** p, uint16_t class_id) {}
11749 
11750  // Intended for serialization/deserialization checking: insert, or
11751  // check for the presence of, a tag at this position in the stream.
11752  // Also used for marking up GC roots in heap snapshots.
11753  virtual void Synchronize(VisitorSynchronization::SyncTag tag) {}
11754 };

11757 // BooleanBit is a helper class for setting and getting a bit in an integer.
11758 class BooleanBit : public AllStatic {
11759  public:
11760  static inline bool get(int value, int bit_position) {
11761  return (value & (1 << bit_position)) != 0;
11762  }
11763 
11764  static inline int set(int value, int bit_position, bool v) {
11765  if (v) {
11766  value |= (1 << bit_position);
11767  } else {
11768  value &= ~(1 << bit_position);
11769  }
11770  return value;
11771  }
11772 };
11773 
11774 
11775 } // NOLINT, false-positive due to second-order macros.
11776 } // NOLINT, false-positive due to second-order macros.
